00:43.640 --> 00:46.837
There was a demon that lived in the air.

00:47.320 --> 00:51.154
They said whoever challenged him
would die.

00:52.600 --> 00:54.511
Their controls would freeze up.

00:54.640 --> 00:57.074
Their planes would buffet wildly...

00:58.040 --> 00:59.951
...and they would disintegrate.

01:04.280 --> 01:07.158
The demon lived at Mach 1 on the meter...

01:07.560 --> 01:09.869
... 750 miles an hour...

01:10.200 --> 01:13.237
...where the air could no longer
move out of the way.

01:14.320 --> 01:19.394
He lived behind a barrier through
which they said no man could ever pass.

01:21.080 --> 01:24.436
They called it the sound barrier.

01:26.840 --> 01:28.796
Then they built a small plane...

01:28.920 --> 01:32.356
...the X-1, to try and break
the sound barrier.

01:33.360 --> 01:37.558
And men came to the high desert
of California to ride it.

01:41.240 --> 01:43.629
They were called test pilots...

01:45.240 --> 01:47.549
...and no one knew their names.

02:02.680 --> 02:05.558
Okay, Whiskey Kilo 28, prepare to drop.

02:05.680 --> 02:08.399
Roger, Ground Control.
This is Whiskey Kilo 28...

02:08.479 --> 02:10.835
...lowering and launching...now.

02:22.680 --> 02:24.591
Mach .92.

02:27.960 --> 02:29.871
.93.

02:33.080 --> 02:34.354
.94.

02:35.400 --> 02:37.391
Hit a mild buffet there.

02:39.480 --> 02:41.072
Mach .95.

02:55.160 --> 02:56.434
.98!

02:59.920 --> 03:01.194
.99!

03:02.640 --> 03:05.359
WK 28, do you want
to declare an emergency?

03:05.680 --> 03:08.069
Negative. WK 28 is not--

03:33.360 --> 03:35.112
Go away.

03:49.000 --> 03:51.560
"The men who fly

03:52.520 --> 03:55.478
"Through the great spaces

03:56.320 --> 03:58.675
"In the sky.

04:00.240 --> 04:02.959
"Be with them always

04:04.080 --> 04:06.389
"In the air

04:07.000 --> 04:11.835
"In darkening storms or sunlight fair.

04:16.079 --> 04:20.949
"Hear us when we lift our prayer

04:23.800 --> 04:28.271
"For all in peril

04:28.760 --> 04:32.150
"In the air."

07:17.080 --> 07:19.355
I was looking at the pictures on your wall.

07:19.440 --> 07:20.998
How come a fancy pilot...

07:21.080 --> 07:24.277
...like Slick there,
doesn't have his picture up there?

07:24.880 --> 07:27.599
What do you have to do
to get your picture up there?

07:27.680 --> 07:29.477
You have to die.

07:32.920 --> 07:35.480
Well, Yeager, you old bastard.

07:36.160 --> 07:40.870
Don't just stand in the doorway
like some lonesome sheepherder.

07:41.080 --> 07:43.116
Get your ass over here and have a drink.

07:43.200 --> 07:44.758
I got you something.

07:55.000 --> 07:56.638
You could be the first.

07:56.760 --> 07:59.638
The man who breaks the sound barrier
will be on top.

08:00.120 --> 08:01.678
You'd be the one they remembered.

08:01.760 --> 08:04.433
You're the best civilian pilot around.

08:05.880 --> 08:07.359
You get that helmet?

08:10.360 --> 08:11.634
It might work.

08:11.880 --> 08:13.677
I'll look like the Galloping Ghost in it.

08:13.760 --> 08:16.797
Some people say the sound barrier
can't be broke.

08:17.480 --> 08:19.994
An engineer will tell you it's an absolute...

08:20.080 --> 08:22.150
...like the firmness of the earth.

08:22.720 --> 08:25.712
The sound barrier is a farm
you can buy in the sky.

08:26.040 --> 08:29.077
The controls will freeze up.
You can't budge the stick.

08:29.160 --> 08:31.799
Anybody tries to break it will auger in.

08:33.720 --> 08:36.280
Well now, maybe it can't be broke.

08:37.400 --> 08:38.674
Then again...

08:39.960 --> 08:41.393
...maybe it can.

08:43.120 --> 08:47.159
Maybe it can only be broke
for a specified sum.

08:48.880 --> 08:50.029
How much?

08:52.280 --> 08:54.669
$150,000.

08:55.040 --> 08:57.508
Come on, Slick, give us a break.

08:59.160 --> 09:01.720
Non-negotiable, as usual.

09:07.160 --> 09:08.559
What do we do now?

09:08.760 --> 09:10.591
That guy in the corner....

09:11.160 --> 09:12.559
Yeager is his name.

09:12.640 --> 09:15.871
He's some kind of a war hero.
Shot down five Germans in one day.

09:15.960 --> 09:18.349
He's a natural-born stick-and-rudder man.

09:18.680 --> 09:21.558
As press-liaison man for the Air Force,
I think....

09:22.200 --> 09:23.952
Any problems with him?

09:24.280 --> 09:25.759
-Only one.
-What's that?

09:26.360 --> 09:27.793
Holding him back.

09:36.280 --> 09:39.955
We were just talking to Slick
about the sound barrier.

09:41.080 --> 09:43.753
We feel that the X-1
is ready to have a go at it.

09:43.840 --> 09:47.310
We think the X-1's got the answer
to go beyond Mach 1.

09:47.760 --> 09:49.398
If there is any beyond.

09:52.080 --> 09:53.832
So, what do you think?

09:54.720 --> 09:58.395
I'll tell you. Half these engineers
have never been off the ground.

09:58.480 --> 10:01.836
They might tell you that
the sound barrier's a brick wall.

10:01.920 --> 10:04.832
It'll rip your ears off
if you try to go through it.

10:05.040 --> 10:08.237
If you ask me,
I don't believe the damn thing even exists.

10:08.400 --> 10:10.470
Waitress, a drink for Mr. Yeager.

10:10.560 --> 10:12.073
No thanks, I got one.

10:12.920 --> 10:15.434
So, do you think
you want to have a go at it?

10:15.760 --> 10:16.875
I might.

10:17.360 --> 10:21.831
But since, as you say,
this sound barrier doesn't really exist...

10:22.680 --> 10:23.908
...how much--

10:24.080 --> 10:25.433
How much you got?

10:26.320 --> 10:29.471
Just joking.
The Air Force is already paying me. Right?

10:31.600 --> 10:32.999
So when do we go?

10:34.000 --> 10:35.752
How about tomorrow morning?

10:36.680 --> 10:37.908
I'll be there.

10:38.800 --> 10:40.279
See you there.

10:43.280 --> 10:45.111
How much are you paying him?

10:45.520 --> 10:47.909
I think it's $283.

10:48.240 --> 10:49.309
A week?

10:49.440 --> 10:50.793
A month.

10:51.280 --> 10:52.793
Well, that's not bad.

10:57.920 --> 11:00.559
First fellow to break the sound barrier...

11:00.680 --> 11:03.433
...gets a free steak with all the trimmings.

11:06.120 --> 11:08.395
I'll have mine medium rare, please.

11:16.000 --> 11:18.798
Honey, you ever been caught
on the desert alone?

11:23.200 --> 11:24.633
I never have.

11:26.960 --> 11:28.871
I don't think I ever will.

11:31.360 --> 11:34.158
Never met the man
who could catch me out there.

11:34.480 --> 11:35.913
I'm half jackrabbit.

11:39.080 --> 11:40.718
Forget it, flyboy.

11:41.600 --> 11:43.909
You'd never catch me.

11:44.720 --> 11:46.153
I believe I will.

11:47.600 --> 11:49.192
Can't be done.

12:07.760 --> 12:09.671
Could I ask you something?

12:12.080 --> 12:13.672
Forget it, sweetie.

12:14.480 --> 12:15.913
She's his wife.

12:35.280 --> 12:37.271
Glennis! I'm gonna get you!

12:39.480 --> 12:40.959
Come back here!

14:03.320 --> 14:05.390
What have you two been up to?

14:06.840 --> 14:08.273
Where's Ridley?

14:08.600 --> 14:10.352
Over there waiting on you.

14:14.840 --> 14:16.273
Can I talk to you?

14:19.320 --> 14:21.550
I got a little problem.

14:23.320 --> 14:26.949
A horse threw me last night
and I dinged up my goddamn ribs.

14:27.200 --> 14:28.189
How bad?

14:28.280 --> 14:31.158
I feel like I broke a couple
of the sons of bitches.

14:31.800 --> 14:35.315
I won't be able to lean over
to shut the door. Got any ideas?

14:35.480 --> 14:36.913
Your left side okay?

14:38.960 --> 14:42.748
I don't want these guys to know.
They'll find somebody else to fly this thing.

14:42.840 --> 14:44.671
I'll try to fix you a handle.

14:52.800 --> 14:55.075
Can you help me out?
I got a small emergency.

14:55.160 --> 14:59.233
I need to borrow your broom handle.
Just hold this right here.

15:07.960 --> 15:09.473
I think that'll work.

15:23.960 --> 15:25.712
Punch a hole in the sky.

15:27.000 --> 15:28.433
I'll be right back.

15:33.800 --> 15:35.074
How are you feeling?

15:35.160 --> 15:36.673
Oh, just about right.

16:35.640 --> 16:39.315
There she is, partner.
All bridled, saddled and ready to go.

16:40.600 --> 16:42.192
You got any Beemans?

16:42.440 --> 16:43.953
Yeah, I got a stick.

16:44.120 --> 16:46.076
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

16:46.160 --> 16:47.309
Fair enough.

17:01.360 --> 17:05.035
Stick this in the handle.
Take your good arm and just whang it.

17:05.920 --> 17:07.353
Okay, thanks, buddy.

18:24.680 --> 18:26.477
Pre-drop checklist complete.

18:26.800 --> 18:28.552
Ten...nine....

18:38.560 --> 18:39.549
Drop!

18:43.080 --> 18:44.638
There you go, buddy.

18:48.960 --> 18:51.110
Put your spurs to her, Chuck.

19:16.280 --> 19:17.998
Mach .91.

19:34.960 --> 19:35.995
.92.

19:40.800 --> 19:42.153
.93.

19:47.600 --> 19:49.192
Hit a mild buffet there.

19:49.440 --> 19:51.192
Just the usual instability.

19:52.720 --> 19:55.280
Ridley, make a note here,
would you, if you got...

19:55.360 --> 19:58.477
...nothing better to do.
Elevator effectiveness regained.

20:06.160 --> 20:07.752
.95.

20:11.280 --> 20:12.838
.96.

20:18.560 --> 20:19.754
More buffeting.

20:20.840 --> 20:22.068
More commotion.

20:22.240 --> 20:23.753
Getting wobbly here.

20:27.680 --> 20:28.829
.98.

20:29.800 --> 20:31.472
She's getting real active.

20:40.360 --> 20:41.475
.99!

20:52.040 --> 20:53.473
What's that sound?

20:59.800 --> 21:01.552
He bought the farm.

21:04.080 --> 21:06.355
That's it. We're back to square one.

21:08.800 --> 21:09.994
Wait a minute.

21:17.480 --> 21:19.869
Ridley, make another note, would you?

21:20.760 --> 21:23.149
Must be something wrong
with the Machmeter.

21:23.240 --> 21:24.992
Jumped plumb off the scale.

21:25.640 --> 21:27.232
Gone screwy on me.

21:27.560 --> 21:29.630
You bust it, we'll fix it.

21:29.840 --> 21:32.229
Personally, I think you're seeing things.

21:34.760 --> 21:38.275
Could be. I'm still going upstairs
like a bat out of hell.

21:42.920 --> 21:44.194
We did it!

21:44.840 --> 21:47.149
We finally broke the sound barrier.

21:47.720 --> 21:48.994
We did it!

22:25.280 --> 22:28.078
I want to place a long-distance call
to Los Angeles.

22:28.160 --> 22:29.513
Who are you calling?

22:29.600 --> 22:30.635
The press!

22:30.720 --> 22:34.076
This is big news.
The sound barrier's been broken.

22:34.160 --> 22:35.832
No, sir. No press.

22:36.160 --> 22:38.720
No word of this goes beyond the flight line.

22:38.880 --> 22:42.555
What's going on? This is big news.
We need coverage of this.

22:42.640 --> 22:44.471
No, sir. Sorry, no press.

22:44.560 --> 22:46.949
Those are orders. National security.

22:47.040 --> 22:48.473
But the war's over!

22:48.800 --> 22:51.837
Look, pal, maybe they don't want
someone to know.

22:52.160 --> 22:53.309
Who?

22:53.520 --> 22:54.953
The Russians, maybe.

22:55.120 --> 22:57.190
But they're our allies!

22:57.520 --> 23:02.310
Well, anyway, someone figured it out
that way, and that's the way it is.

23:03.440 --> 23:04.953
Chuck, you're our man!

23:05.840 --> 23:07.478
You're the fastest man alive!

23:07.560 --> 23:09.391
We want you to fly more planes for us.

23:09.480 --> 23:11.914
We want you to fly all our planes!

23:12.560 --> 23:14.949
What you been doing, hedgehopping?

23:53.680 --> 23:55.318
Word will get out, Major.

23:55.400 --> 23:57.994
Maybe not to the press
or the general public.

23:58.320 --> 24:02.393
But soon, every fighter jock, rocket ace,
and rat-racer in the country...

24:02.480 --> 24:06.951
...will be headed this way, wanting
to push the outside of the envelope...

24:07.440 --> 24:10.318
...and get to the top of the pyramid.

24:35.600 --> 24:37.750
Edwards Air Force Base.

24:37.840 --> 24:39.717
This is the place to be, hon.

24:39.840 --> 24:43.150
They're going faster, farther
and higher here than anywhere else.

24:48.560 --> 24:50.630
I'll tell you something else, too.

24:50.800 --> 24:55.237
We'll climb right up that ladder,
just like we did at Langley.

24:56.080 --> 24:57.035
We?

24:58.160 --> 24:59.434
You mean you.

25:00.240 --> 25:01.992
Hon, we're a team!

25:02.320 --> 25:04.276
I move up, you move up.

25:04.840 --> 25:06.990
Right to the top of the old pyramid.

25:08.720 --> 25:09.914
Slow down, Gordo.

25:10.000 --> 25:12.275
Come on now, you're scaring the girls.

25:12.400 --> 25:15.437
You're scaring the girls. You are!

25:20.560 --> 25:22.949
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

25:24.880 --> 25:26.950
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

25:33.200 --> 25:35.111
You're looking at him, baby.

25:39.120 --> 25:40.712
Come on, cheer up.

25:41.520 --> 25:44.034
Hey, have I ever let you down?

28:34.360 --> 28:37.158
Deke, that's 62 men...

28:37.600 --> 28:39.477
...in the last 36 weeks.

28:41.080 --> 28:42.911
You know what that averages?

28:46.320 --> 28:48.754
Is that Gus Grissom from Langley Field?

28:50.040 --> 28:52.918
What is an ace like you
doing in a place like this?

28:53.000 --> 28:55.070
Well, if it ain't Hot Dog.

28:55.960 --> 28:57.154
Gordo...

28:58.080 --> 28:59.672
-...Cooper, right?
-Yeah.

29:00.440 --> 29:04.274
Gordo thinks he's one of those
hot-dog pilots you hear so much about.

29:04.600 --> 29:06.352
You got a short memory.

29:06.520 --> 29:10.798
I am not one of them hot-dog pilots.
I am the Hot Dog Man himself.

29:11.240 --> 29:15.119
I guess you're too shy to tell this guy
how I used to wax your tail.

29:17.680 --> 29:18.954
Wax my tail?

29:20.720 --> 29:22.950
Hot Dog, you were just in my shadow.

29:23.760 --> 29:25.671
That's where you'll always be.

29:25.920 --> 29:28.229
What are you two rookies going to have?

29:29.360 --> 29:30.315
Rookies?

29:32.560 --> 29:34.471
Now hold on, sis.

29:35.280 --> 29:38.397
You are looking
at a whole new ballgame here now.

29:39.800 --> 29:42.598
In a few years I bet you're even
going to immortalize us...

29:42.680 --> 29:45.433
...by putting our pictures up there
on your wall.

29:50.960 --> 29:53.190
Did I say something wrong?

29:53.640 --> 29:57.030
I'll tell you. We got two categories
of pilots around here.

29:57.520 --> 30:00.717
We got your prime pilots
that get all the hot planes.

30:00.840 --> 30:04.719
And we got your pudknockers
who dream about getting the hot planes.

30:05.760 --> 30:08.832
Now what are you two pudknockers
going to have?

30:13.840 --> 30:15.114
Scotch.

30:17.040 --> 30:19.759
You know what happened!
The machine broke.

30:19.840 --> 30:21.034
Not the machine, it's the man.

30:21.120 --> 30:24.396
He was dead before he went up.
Don't talk about it here.

30:44.400 --> 30:46.630
Good one. Now fire it in here.

30:48.120 --> 30:49.599
Look at old Yeager.

30:50.320 --> 30:53.517
On top of the pyramid
for five goddamn years.

30:54.160 --> 30:57.197
Every time somebody goes faster,
he just goes up again.

30:58.320 --> 31:00.550
He stays the fastest man alive.

31:05.800 --> 31:07.074
You know...

31:07.680 --> 31:08.908
...sometimes...

31:09.760 --> 31:12.877
...all it takes is just the sound
of a truck starting.

31:14.440 --> 31:15.475
I think:

31:16.240 --> 31:17.878
"That's the crash truck."

31:24.400 --> 31:25.389
Anyway...

31:26.160 --> 31:28.230
...I'm really glad we could talk.

31:28.880 --> 31:31.872
I thought I was the only one
who had these nightmares.

31:33.400 --> 31:34.549
Yeah, me too.

31:35.400 --> 31:38.631
Nobody ever wants to talk
about anything around here.

31:38.960 --> 31:40.871
Everybody's always trying to...

31:42.160 --> 31:44.879
..."maintain an even strain."

31:46.480 --> 31:50.758
Well, you marry a fighter jock
and you marry the military.

31:52.240 --> 31:53.832
I'll tell you one thing.

31:54.320 --> 31:56.880
The military owes me for all this.

31:57.320 --> 31:59.754
One day I expect the military
to make good.

32:04.560 --> 32:07.597
Well, it sure ain't your average dull life.

32:09.040 --> 32:10.837
I went East for a reunion...

32:10.920 --> 32:14.151
...and all my friends could talk about
was their husbands' work.

32:14.240 --> 32:18.472
How dog-eat-dog and cutthroat it was
on Madison Avenue...

32:19.400 --> 32:20.879
...places like that.

32:23.920 --> 32:25.512
Cutthroat?

32:27.280 --> 32:29.840
I wondered how they would have felt...

32:30.800 --> 32:33.837
...if each time their husband
went in to make a deal...

32:34.160 --> 32:37.948
...there was a one in four chance
he wouldn't come out of the meeting.

32:42.760 --> 32:45.479
I'm going home to my folks in San Diego.

32:48.600 --> 32:50.033
What did Gordo say?

32:51.160 --> 32:53.549
He "maintained an even strain."

32:59.160 --> 33:00.309
Look at them.

33:01.880 --> 33:04.348
You'd think they were talking about sports.

33:11.160 --> 33:12.115
Men....

33:13.440 --> 33:16.432
Sometimes they're just such...assholes.

33:29.080 --> 33:31.753
Sometimes they sure are
handy assholes, though.

33:32.440 --> 33:33.839
Yeah, sometimes....

33:36.040 --> 33:37.393
Sometimes.

33:41.920 --> 33:43.433
You want a hot dog?

33:49.560 --> 33:51.471
I'm leaving, Gordo.

33:57.720 --> 33:58.994
Look at that!

33:59.480 --> 34:02.040
Yeah, that's the D-558 Phase 2.

34:02.360 --> 34:03.873
Scott Crossfield.

34:03.960 --> 34:06.520
It sure as hell is. Jesus!

34:09.719 --> 34:11.710
He scorched that one, didn't he?

34:15.159 --> 34:17.310
He's pushing the outside of the envelope.

34:17.400 --> 34:19.311
He must be going for a record.

34:19.400 --> 34:21.469
He's shooting for Mach 2, I heard.

34:24.320 --> 34:28.313
On the 50th anniversary
of the Wright Brothers' historic flight...

34:28.719 --> 34:32.076
...another historic flight takes place,
as Scott Crossfield...

34:32.360 --> 34:36.148
...streaks across the skies
over the high desert in California.

34:36.440 --> 34:37.554
Mach 2.

34:37.639 --> 34:40.473
Almost 1,500 miles per hour...

34:40.600 --> 34:42.830
...and a new world record!

34:43.159 --> 34:45.230
It's a field day for the press.

34:45.560 --> 34:47.949
Congratulations come
from a previous record holder...

34:48.040 --> 34:52.511
...as he shakes the hand
of the fastest man alive, Scott Crossfield.

34:52.880 --> 34:55.792
And there's a comradeship of speed.

34:55.960 --> 34:58.918
To Scott Crossfield, the fastest man alive.

35:17.560 --> 35:19.630
Compliments of Pancho's, Scotty.

35:22.520 --> 35:24.431
The real test wasn't Mach 2.

35:24.760 --> 35:28.799
I guess that demon lives out
at about 2.3 on your Machmeter.

35:29.920 --> 35:32.275
Yeah, but Mach 2 was the magic number.

35:32.760 --> 35:37.038
Like 60 homers, like batting .400,
like the four-minute mile.

35:37.680 --> 35:39.796
The press likes a nice round number.

35:39.960 --> 35:43.077
After that, they don't care,
until the next magic number.

35:43.160 --> 35:46.675
You need more than speed records.
You need coverage.

35:46.920 --> 35:48.114
Coverage?

35:48.440 --> 35:51.955
You mean them root weevils
that crawl around popping off cameras?

35:52.120 --> 35:54.190
Those root weevils write history.

35:54.440 --> 35:58.149
Let them write the history,
and let the pilots fly the planes.

35:59.800 --> 36:00.915
Pilots.

36:24.400 --> 36:26.994
You know what really makes
your rocket ships go up?

36:27.080 --> 36:30.516
The aerodynamics would take
so long to explain to you that--

36:30.680 --> 36:31.669
Funding.

36:31.760 --> 36:33.751
That's what makes your ships go up.

36:33.840 --> 36:35.432
I'll tell you something.

36:36.000 --> 36:37.513
And you guys, too.

36:38.080 --> 36:40.548
No bucks, no Buck Rogers.

36:41.240 --> 36:43.754
Whoever gets the funding
gets the technology.

36:43.840 --> 36:46.673
Whoever gets the technology stays on top.

36:46.760 --> 36:48.398
Flyboy, let's dance.

36:49.160 --> 36:50.673
I'll drink to that.

37:21.880 --> 37:24.553
He'll be going after Crossfield soon,
won't he?

37:24.960 --> 37:26.154
No, he won't.

37:26.320 --> 37:29.517
He'll be going after that demon
that lives in the thin air.

38:08.400 --> 38:09.833
You got any Beemans?

38:10.160 --> 38:13.630
Even before you hit Mach 2,
she'll be unforgiving on you.

38:13.840 --> 38:16.559
So take it easy.
Wring her out a little bit this time.

38:16.640 --> 38:17.675
You got any gum?

38:17.760 --> 38:18.909
Yeah, I got me a stick.

38:19.000 --> 38:21.309
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

38:21.760 --> 38:23.352
-Fair enough.
-Thank you.

38:38.480 --> 38:39.833
Okay, drop her.

38:40.080 --> 38:42.150
All right, here we go again.

38:46.240 --> 38:47.116
Drop!

38:57.280 --> 38:58.918
Number 3 coming on.

39:06.800 --> 39:09.360
Got seven seconds on 150 right now.

39:28.240 --> 39:30.117
I've got you in sight, Chuck.

39:30.760 --> 39:32.273
Going out of sight...

39:32.880 --> 39:33.835
...now!

39:40.360 --> 39:41.634
Mach 1.

39:51.720 --> 39:52.755
Number 4.

39:57.720 --> 39:59.073
Here goes Mach 2.

39:59.560 --> 40:00.675
2. 1.

40:00.920 --> 40:02.194
Sorry, Scotty.

40:03.800 --> 40:05.153
You got her now, buddy.

40:05.240 --> 40:06.753
You can ease it back.

40:07.720 --> 40:08.994
Bring it on in.

40:09.160 --> 40:10.798
I'm pushing the envelope.

40:12.120 --> 40:13.838
See where that demon lives.

40:33.400 --> 40:35.311
Come in, Chuck.

40:37.280 --> 40:38.679
Say again. Over.

40:38.760 --> 40:40.557
Do you read? Over.

40:42.920 --> 40:45.480
Damn! He's uncorked it!

40:46.240 --> 40:47.559
Mayday! Mayday!

40:47.720 --> 40:49.472
Alert all ground crews.

40:53.960 --> 40:55.552
Talk to me!

41:02.120 --> 41:03.075
Come in!

41:05.720 --> 41:07.631
Do you read me? Over.

41:18.800 --> 41:20.518
I'm fighting bad here.

41:22.280 --> 41:25.317
I'm down to 25,000 over Tehachapi.

41:28.840 --> 41:31.638
I don't know if I can make it
back to base or not.

41:32.840 --> 41:34.114
What happened?

41:34.240 --> 41:36.834
Think I bust the canopy with my head.

41:37.160 --> 41:38.673
I'm getting okay now.

41:41.320 --> 41:44.198
We sure chased that old demon this time.

41:45.160 --> 41:47.116
That's as fast as a man can go.

41:49.000 --> 41:50.592
What's next, Ridley?

42:28.880 --> 42:30.074
It's called Sputnik.

42:30.160 --> 42:32.037
We know. Sit down.

42:37.640 --> 42:39.551
And as I was saying...

42:40.280 --> 42:43.795
...whoever controls
the high ground of space...

42:44.280 --> 42:45.998
...will control the world.

42:46.720 --> 42:50.679
The Roman Empire controlled
the world because it could build roads.

42:51.040 --> 42:54.669
Later, the British Empire was dominant
because it had ships.

42:56.040 --> 42:59.749
In the air stage, we were powerful
because we had the airplane.

43:01.200 --> 43:04.556
Now the Communists have established
a foothold in outer space.

43:05.080 --> 43:08.470
Soon they'll have space platforms
to drop nuclear bombs on us...

43:08.560 --> 43:10.790
...like rocks from a highway overpass.

43:11.280 --> 43:14.158
How the hell did they get ahead of us?

43:14.280 --> 43:16.236
Gentlemen, I think we're ready.

43:21.600 --> 43:24.068
Is there a loose plug over there anywhere?

43:26.720 --> 43:28.358
Here it is. I'll get it.

43:28.560 --> 43:31.120
Senator Johnson's right.
This is Armageddon.

43:31.440 --> 43:34.238
The decisive battle between
the forces of good and evil.

43:34.320 --> 43:37.039
We're engaged in a struggle for survival.

43:39.360 --> 43:41.555
This footage was assembled from...

43:41.800 --> 43:44.712
...sources operating under deep cover
at great risk.

43:45.800 --> 43:49.076
We're fortunate this material
did not perish with a couple of men.

43:49.160 --> 43:52.277
This is secret footage
of the Russian Korabl rocket...

43:52.360 --> 43:56.069
...and these are the German scientists
that they captured after the war.

43:56.160 --> 43:59.197
Was it their German scientists
who got them up there first?

44:01.000 --> 44:02.638
No, it was not, Senator.

44:02.720 --> 44:05.393
Our Germans are better
than their Germans.

44:05.920 --> 44:08.912
That's Titov on the right
and on the left is Gagarin.

44:09.040 --> 44:11.759
No, Titov's on the left.
Gagarin's on the right.

44:13.480 --> 44:15.869
They bear a great resemblance
to each other.

44:15.960 --> 44:20.397
If the Soviets ever do put a man up there,
it will be one of these two.

44:20.560 --> 44:22.471
Most likely, the one on the left.

44:22.560 --> 44:23.834
-Gagarin.
-Titov.

44:25.360 --> 44:26.873
Isn't that their chief designer?

44:26.960 --> 44:28.473
We know very little about him.

44:28.560 --> 44:31.028
-Let us see him again.
-Here's some more of him.

44:31.120 --> 44:34.078
They've developed a program
of stupendous dimensions...

44:34.160 --> 44:36.628
...and he is clearly the genius behind it.

44:38.560 --> 44:41.028
I, for one, do not intend to go to sleep...

44:41.360 --> 44:43.590
...by the light of a Communist moon.

44:47.200 --> 44:49.270
Get that moron off of there!

44:53.200 --> 44:55.919
We could have orbited
a satellite a year ago...

44:56.000 --> 44:58.036
...if we had been given a green light.

44:58.120 --> 45:01.715
Now we must get something up there
quick and dirty, any way at all.

45:01.840 --> 45:02.955
Well, what?

45:03.280 --> 45:07.034
By combining our available rockets,
the Redstone, the Atlas...

45:07.320 --> 45:09.629
...I agree that we could launch a pod.

45:10.560 --> 45:11.629
A pot?

45:11.760 --> 45:12.715
A pod.

45:13.200 --> 45:14.474
A capsule.

45:14.560 --> 45:17.120
Now, we will be in full control of this pod.

45:17.280 --> 45:19.475
It will go up like a cannonball...

45:19.560 --> 45:21.994
...and come down like a cannonball...

45:22.320 --> 45:24.709
...splashing down in the ocean...

45:24.920 --> 45:28.276
...with a parachute to spare the life
of the specimen inside.

45:29.200 --> 45:30.474
Spaceman?

45:30.800 --> 45:31.949
Specimen.

45:34.120 --> 45:36.236
Well, what kind of "specimen"?

45:37.720 --> 45:38.789
A tough one.

45:39.920 --> 45:41.558
Responsive to orders.

45:42.920 --> 45:44.558
I had in mind a jimp.

45:45.120 --> 45:46.075
"Jimp"?

45:46.320 --> 45:48.197
Well, what the hell is a "jimp"?

45:48.560 --> 45:51.836
A jimp. A jimpanzee, Senator. An ape.

45:52.480 --> 45:56.155
The first American into space
is not going to be a chimpanzee.

45:57.640 --> 46:00.393
Who would you put into space,
Mr. President?

46:00.520 --> 46:04.308
We have film of some people
we think are strong candidates.

46:04.400 --> 46:07.437
We'd like to run it by you
and stimulate some thinking.

46:08.880 --> 46:12.555
These are people we felt
would be excellent in the splashdown.

46:12.760 --> 46:14.557
We like the one on the right.

46:14.640 --> 46:17.916
-No, on the left.
-On the right. Don't embarrass me!

46:18.000 --> 46:22.357
These people are very experienced with
machinery and have their own helmets.

46:22.640 --> 46:23.868
Is that a factor?

46:23.960 --> 46:25.359
As you'll see...

46:25.760 --> 46:28.672
...they're quite comfortable
in conditions of flame.

46:29.640 --> 46:33.792
Now this is personnel who have
very well-developed equilibrium.

46:35.400 --> 46:37.868
Good middle ear. Also very nice people.

46:37.960 --> 46:39.188
Very easy to work with.

46:39.280 --> 46:42.192
With some work,
they could be very responsive to orders.

46:42.280 --> 46:45.033
This is my first choice.
The man with the hood.

46:45.160 --> 46:49.631
Since he works without eyesight,
his other senses are sharpened.

46:49.800 --> 46:53.031
In space there'll be little need
for eyeballing at any rate.

46:53.120 --> 46:55.714
The cannonball effect you mentioned....

46:56.000 --> 46:58.673
We were basically thinking about...

46:58.760 --> 47:00.716
...putting a couple into orbit.

47:00.960 --> 47:03.076
Possibly adds emotional stability.

47:03.720 --> 47:06.996
This individual combines many
plus factors that we mentioned.

47:07.080 --> 47:10.993
Ease with flames, comfort at heights
and agility in the splashdown phase.

47:11.080 --> 47:13.355
Also, he is available as of the 15th.

47:15.640 --> 47:17.437
I want test pilots!

47:18.080 --> 47:20.196
Test pilots? No, you can't deal with them.

47:20.280 --> 47:23.317
I'm sure we can do better
with another type of man...

47:23.520 --> 47:25.192
...any other type of man.

47:25.440 --> 47:27.078
A more manageable type.

47:27.200 --> 47:29.111
It will only complicate things.

47:29.200 --> 47:31.634
With a man we must guarantee
a safe return.

47:31.720 --> 47:34.598
Mr. President, I think
you'd be wise to reconsider.

47:36.360 --> 47:37.509
Test pilots?

47:37.640 --> 47:39.312
We'll be heading for some air bases.

47:39.400 --> 47:40.992
Not just some air bases.

47:41.200 --> 47:44.510
The one with the great test pilots.
There's only one place to go.

47:45.760 --> 47:49.150
I was there once before
and I hoped I'd never have to go back.

47:49.720 --> 47:53.952
It's a god-forsaken spot on the roof
of the high desert in California.

47:54.440 --> 47:57.796
A prehistoric throwback
of an airfield called Edwards.

47:58.120 --> 48:00.680
They've got a weird, mad-monk squadron.

48:01.080 --> 48:03.640
They live in rat shacks, terrible conditions.

48:03.720 --> 48:06.917
Corrugated tin, bare bones, low rent.

48:07.640 --> 48:09.551
This is the joint they hang out in.

48:09.640 --> 48:11.710
Pancho's Happy Bottom Riding Club.

48:12.040 --> 48:14.270
It's called Happy Bottom Riding Club?

48:14.600 --> 48:16.511
How'd it get a name like that?

48:16.960 --> 48:18.279
Ask Pancho.

48:21.320 --> 48:24.630
We're meeting the Liaison Officer.
They are expecting us.

48:24.720 --> 48:26.278
They? Who's "they"?

48:26.480 --> 48:27.629
The best--

48:30.280 --> 48:32.350
The best test pilots in the world.

48:33.400 --> 48:35.470
They got some kind of brotherhood.

48:36.600 --> 48:38.670
They think they got the right stuff.

48:38.760 --> 48:40.830
What stuff? Heroism, bravery?

48:41.160 --> 48:42.991
There any snakes around here?

48:43.080 --> 48:44.593
Yeah. In the bushes.

48:44.880 --> 48:48.668
Heroism and bravery are part of it.
But seems to be more to it.

48:49.160 --> 48:50.673
What do they say it means?

48:50.760 --> 48:53.638
They don't say anything.
They don't talk about it.

48:53.720 --> 48:55.870
They don't talk about it to outsiders?

48:56.080 --> 48:57.399
To each other.

48:57.480 --> 48:59.471
To outsiders they say even less.

49:00.680 --> 49:02.318
Anyway, they're all here.

49:02.800 --> 49:04.916
Including the ace of aces himself.

49:05.000 --> 49:06.115
Who's that?

49:07.080 --> 49:08.069
Yeager.

49:08.560 --> 49:09.959
Never heard of him.

49:23.480 --> 49:26.153
These must be our gentlemen
from Washington...

49:26.440 --> 49:28.192
...scouting for astronauts.

49:31.000 --> 49:33.309
Scouting for lab rabbits, more likely.

49:34.120 --> 49:35.712
I didn't quite hear you.

49:38.080 --> 49:39.718
I said, "Lab rabbits."

49:40.920 --> 49:42.035
What's that mean?

49:42.120 --> 49:44.839
It means you don't need
honest-to-God pilots.

49:45.320 --> 49:49.154
What you ought to get is a lab rabbit
to curl up in your damn capsule...

49:49.600 --> 49:51.431
...with its heart beating...

49:51.680 --> 49:53.318
...and a wire up the kazoo.

49:55.760 --> 49:56.954
I don't hold with it.

49:57.040 --> 49:58.314
I don't either.

49:58.720 --> 50:01.234
You want a pilot to be a ballistic missile.

50:01.440 --> 50:02.953
And then splashdown.

50:03.400 --> 50:05.311
Possibly get lost at sea.

50:05.440 --> 50:07.670
There's some things you can't change.

50:08.320 --> 50:10.629
Some peckerwood's
got to take the beast up.

50:10.720 --> 50:13.917
And some peckerwood's got to land it.

50:14.400 --> 50:17.756
And that peckerwood is called a pilot.

50:18.400 --> 50:19.879
You're mighty right.

50:20.080 --> 50:22.548
The boys smell panic in your program.

50:22.720 --> 50:24.915
That's one thing they don't respond to.

50:25.000 --> 50:29.198
Now maybe if we talk privately
to Yeager and some of the other boys--

50:29.280 --> 50:30.474
That's Yeager?

50:30.560 --> 50:33.757
Anybody goes up in the damn thing's
gonna be Spam in a can.

50:39.280 --> 50:41.236
Yeager doesn't fit the profile.

50:42.200 --> 50:45.590
He didn't go to college.
We're only taking college personnel.

50:46.240 --> 50:50.711
Forget about Walker and Crossfield
and the other civilian pilots, too.

50:52.920 --> 50:56.276
The security clearance just takes
too long with those people.

50:56.640 --> 50:59.359
Besides, they seem
a little too independent.

51:00.960 --> 51:03.155
You mean for this space race...

51:03.800 --> 51:05.836
...you don't want our best pilots?

51:06.240 --> 51:07.673
I didn't say that.

51:08.160 --> 51:11.357
We want the best pilots that we can get.

51:14.120 --> 51:15.712
Y'all want some whiskey?

51:16.200 --> 51:18.555
No, thanks, Fred. Just a little coffee.

51:18.960 --> 51:20.632
I'd like a Coca-Cola.

51:21.480 --> 51:22.833
In a clean glass.

51:23.280 --> 51:26.511
There's an old saying:
"Never refuse a combat assignment."

51:29.120 --> 51:33.750
Well, there sure is a long line
of shit-hot rocket aces around here.

51:35.240 --> 51:36.389
Hey, Hot Dog.

51:37.600 --> 51:39.989
What the hell's "astronaut" mean anyway?

51:43.200 --> 51:44.474
Star voyager.

51:48.960 --> 51:50.871
Star voyager Gus Grissom.

51:53.280 --> 51:55.032
I like the sound of that.

51:56.440 --> 51:57.589
Now your name is?

51:57.920 --> 51:59.672
My name, José Jiménez.

52:02.240 --> 52:04.959
Who are we gonna get
to take on the Russians?

52:05.440 --> 52:08.955
Have you seen this José Jiménez?
He's a crack-up.

52:10.880 --> 52:14.714
I am the chief astronaut
of the United States Interplanetary....

52:21.440 --> 52:23.351
My name, José Jiménez.

52:24.280 --> 52:27.431
Now I see you have some of
your space equipment with you.

52:27.720 --> 52:30.075
What is that called? The crash helmet?

52:30.400 --> 52:31.992
Oh, I hope not.

52:32.360 --> 52:33.679
Get that guy off.

52:34.120 --> 52:36.350
The country's already laughing at us.

52:39.360 --> 52:41.032
This is the show I wanted you to see.

52:41.120 --> 52:42.394
Who, that kid?

52:45.480 --> 52:47.755
Winner of five
Distinguished Flying Crosses...

52:47.840 --> 52:52.311
...and holder of the coast-to-coast,
nonstop, supersonic flight record...

52:52.640 --> 52:54.631
...from the U.S. Marine Corps...

52:55.040 --> 52:56.359
...Major John Glenn!

52:56.440 --> 52:57.429
That guy.

53:01.600 --> 53:03.875
Can you tell us what's that song?

53:06.080 --> 53:07.991
Straighten Up and Fly Right.

53:16.640 --> 53:18.756
It's Straighten Up and Fly Right.

53:19.520 --> 53:20.714
He's not dumb.

53:27.640 --> 53:31.633
Major, Eddie here has a little problem
with his girlfriend.

53:32.120 --> 53:35.157
Did you ever have a problem like that
when you were ten?

53:35.560 --> 53:37.073
Yes, I did, Bob.

53:37.840 --> 53:39.910
I liked a girl in my class, but...

53:40.280 --> 53:43.158
...the other guys liked her too
and she didn't pay attention.

53:43.240 --> 53:45.390
But I kept after her, Eddie.

53:46.400 --> 53:48.675
Did you finally get her to notice you?

53:48.760 --> 53:49.875
Yes, I did.

53:50.200 --> 53:52.509
In fact, I finally got her to marry me.

53:57.280 --> 53:58.633
They love the guy.

54:15.200 --> 54:17.555
Delta Charlie 9, you are clear to land...

54:17.640 --> 54:19.198
...at 180 degrees.

54:19.800 --> 54:22.473
José Jiménez on approach.

54:24.920 --> 54:27.309
My name, José Jiménez.

54:27.640 --> 54:32.031
Yeah, Shepard, I forgot.
You are clear at 180 degrees.

54:32.360 --> 54:35.875
Some boys here want to talk to you
about being an astronaut.

54:36.120 --> 54:39.476
They want to make me an astronaut?
Oh, I hope not.

54:51.000 --> 54:54.436
Are you sure the Navy's got good pilots?

54:55.720 --> 54:59.633
They call them aviators in the Navy.
They say they're better than pilots.

55:11.000 --> 55:13.560
Gentlemen, I'd like you
to meet Alan Shepard.

55:15.160 --> 55:17.390
I'd like you to meet Alan Shepard.

55:17.560 --> 55:19.391
Just the man we came to see.

55:26.080 --> 55:28.036
You've heard about our project.

55:28.120 --> 55:31.317
We're going up against the Russians.
It's got the highest....

55:31.640 --> 55:32.755
Priority.

55:33.080 --> 55:34.513
It's a hazardous...

55:35.000 --> 55:37.878
...undertaking. In fact,
it's extremely hazardous.

55:39.200 --> 55:43.671
It's so hazardous that
if you decide not to volunteer...

55:43.880 --> 55:46.440
...it will not be held against you
in any way.

55:46.760 --> 55:48.478
-Sounds dangerous.
-It is.

55:49.560 --> 55:50.993
Count me in.

55:54.320 --> 55:57.073
There's nothing to worry about.
Absolutely nothing.

56:04.760 --> 56:07.035
Why are you doing this to me?

56:07.640 --> 56:10.837
I'm afraid there's no simple way
to explain that to you.

56:33.720 --> 56:35.790
Thank you, Number 21.

56:48.240 --> 56:50.629
Number 22, please.

56:52.160 --> 56:53.752
You're gonna love it.

57:02.320 --> 57:04.231
Excuse me, are you John Glenn?

57:06.120 --> 57:07.553
Scott Carpenter.

57:08.240 --> 57:10.959
I recognize you from those TV shows.
I like them.

57:11.120 --> 57:12.951
I had a good time doing them.

57:13.040 --> 57:15.918
I guess we're both here
for the same reason.

57:17.880 --> 57:19.950
You know what they've got planned?

57:20.440 --> 57:22.112
No. Let me check it out.

57:22.520 --> 57:24.351
What have you got scheduled?

57:24.480 --> 57:27.472
We're not really free
to reveal all the testing.

57:31.720 --> 57:32.948
I don't get this.

57:33.040 --> 57:35.952
Sending us down here
disguised as civilians.

57:36.200 --> 57:38.760
Come on, Gus, cut it out. What the hell...?

57:38.840 --> 57:42.037
Hot Dog, this entire operation's
supposed to be hush-hush.

57:42.640 --> 57:47.111
We got top-secret orders to blend in
with the patients. So shut up.

57:49.960 --> 57:52.030
There might be Russian agents here.

57:55.440 --> 57:57.829
They don't look very Russian to me, Gus.

57:58.280 --> 58:00.999
All we got here is your local gentry, and...

58:01.840 --> 58:05.435
...then you got Navy
and Marine pilots over here.

58:05.640 --> 58:08.359
None of these guys is up
to Air Force standards.

58:09.160 --> 58:12.994
I hear they got some 50-some guys
trying out for seven spots.

58:13.560 --> 58:16.757
After they pick us three,
there's only gonna be four spots.

58:17.120 --> 58:19.680
Sounds right to me. Where do we go next?

58:19.760 --> 58:21.398
You go in that door.

58:25.360 --> 58:26.679
Who are you?

58:33.080 --> 58:35.878
My name, José Jiménez.

58:39.240 --> 58:40.878
You talking to us, buddy?

58:41.920 --> 58:45.515
All Air Force pilots go in that door.

58:46.640 --> 58:48.153
When they all go in...

58:49.320 --> 58:51.038
...they all look the same.

58:51.480 --> 58:53.596
But when they all come out...

58:54.640 --> 58:56.358
...they all look different.

58:57.040 --> 58:58.109
How's that?

59:00.040 --> 59:01.758
Fellow, I said how's that?

59:03.240 --> 59:05.037
When they all come out...

59:06.440 --> 59:08.271
...they all look scared.

59:18.200 --> 59:19.599
Buenos días, González.

59:21.120 --> 59:22.633
Buenos días yourself.

59:24.000 --> 59:25.592
Would you come this way.

59:30.440 --> 59:32.476
That guy didn't fool me a bit.

59:32.880 --> 59:34.233
That Mexican guy?

59:34.520 --> 59:37.717
That guy's Navy all the way.
There's another swabbo.

59:38.320 --> 59:40.788
I'll open the box a little so you can see.

59:41.160 --> 59:42.513
Don't put your fingers in there.

59:42.600 --> 59:45.160
This thing will bite them off. It's vicious.

59:48.960 --> 59:50.916
Real swabbo sense of humor.

59:53.160 --> 59:56.152
Let's see what there is
to be scared about back here.

01:00:00.280 --> 01:00:04.159
