01:33:04.120 --> 01:33:06.634
The so-called astronaut...

01:33:06.760 --> 01:33:09.877
...would merely be a redundant component.

01:33:12.840 --> 01:33:14.068
And here you can see...

01:33:14.160 --> 01:33:17.596
...these chimps are capable of many
of the same tasks as men.

01:33:18.000 --> 01:33:20.116
And they are much more cooperative.

01:33:24.120 --> 01:33:27.669
They are being put through every phase
of the astronaut training.

01:33:27.880 --> 01:33:31.395
As far as we are concerned,
the question still remains:

01:33:31.640 --> 01:33:33.471
Which one will be first?

01:33:33.800 --> 01:33:35.153
The man or...

01:33:35.400 --> 01:33:36.594
...the monkey?

01:33:37.560 --> 01:33:38.709
We shall see.

01:34:08.920 --> 01:34:10.558
Take it easy with that.

01:34:18.640 --> 01:34:21.279
-Where are you putting the window?
-Window?

01:34:21.680 --> 01:34:22.795
There is no window.

01:34:22.880 --> 01:34:23.995
No window?

01:34:25.320 --> 01:34:26.833
What about the hatch?

01:34:28.200 --> 01:34:31.272
We need a hatch with explosive bolts,
that we can open ourselves.

01:34:31.360 --> 01:34:33.749
There's something you don't understand.

01:34:33.840 --> 01:34:36.149
This is the final form of the capsule.

01:34:36.320 --> 01:34:37.435
No hatch.

01:34:37.600 --> 01:34:40.512
What would happen
if the automatic controls went out?

01:34:40.600 --> 01:34:43.637
With backups, checks,
this would not happen.

01:34:43.880 --> 01:34:46.235
I said, what would happen if it did?

01:34:46.360 --> 01:34:47.998
The pilot would have to fly it back.

01:34:48.080 --> 01:34:49.832
This is the way it is.

01:34:51.000 --> 01:34:54.117
I wonder how the press will feel about this.

01:34:54.200 --> 01:34:57.397
The press? What does the press
have to say about this?

01:34:58.680 --> 01:35:02.036
Do you boys know
what makes this bird go up?

01:35:02.760 --> 01:35:05.035
Funding makes this bird go up.

01:35:05.200 --> 01:35:07.156
That's right. No bucks...

01:35:08.120 --> 01:35:09.473
...no Buck Rogers.

01:35:09.720 --> 01:35:12.154
And the press over there....

01:35:19.520 --> 01:35:21.476
They all want to see Buck Rogers.

01:35:21.560 --> 01:35:22.788
And that's us.

01:35:23.600 --> 01:35:24.749
Buck Rogers.

01:35:25.120 --> 01:35:28.192
You see, those fellows over there
have been making us out...

01:35:28.280 --> 01:35:31.397
...as the seven finest and bravest pilots
in all America.

01:35:32.400 --> 01:35:34.914
If the story would come out in the press...

01:35:36.040 --> 01:35:38.395
...that we are not allowed to fly as pilots....

01:35:38.480 --> 01:35:39.913
We want a window.

01:35:43.120 --> 01:35:45.031
There could maybe be...

01:35:45.240 --> 01:35:48.232
...in future capsules a window...

01:35:49.760 --> 01:35:50.988
...here.

01:35:51.160 --> 01:35:53.913
No, that's where the hatch
with explosive bolts goes.

01:35:54.000 --> 01:35:55.956
The hatch with the explosive--

01:35:59.320 --> 01:36:02.596
There could be a hatch
with explosive bolts on the capsule.

01:36:02.760 --> 01:36:04.671
That is a spacecraft, sir.

01:36:05.560 --> 01:36:07.790
We do not refer to it as a "capsule."

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:11.314
Spacecraft.

01:36:14.040 --> 01:36:16.349
A hatch with explosive bolts on the...

01:36:16.920 --> 01:36:18.194
...spacecraft.

01:36:21.040 --> 01:36:24.589
And there will be pitch and yaw thrusters
to enable the occupant--

01:36:24.680 --> 01:36:25.715
The pilot.

01:36:27.720 --> 01:36:29.119
Astronaut-pilot?

01:36:32.360 --> 01:36:33.634
The astronaut...

01:36:34.680 --> 01:36:35.795
...pilot...

01:36:37.520 --> 01:36:38.873
...to have some...

01:36:39.520 --> 01:36:40.714
...to have...

01:36:43.920 --> 01:36:45.069
...control...

01:36:47.360 --> 01:36:49.271
...of the re-entry procedures.

01:36:54.040 --> 01:36:55.393
We appreciate it.

01:36:55.600 --> 01:36:59.673
You wouldn't mind if we had the press
take a few photos of us, would you?

01:37:31.920 --> 01:37:35.913
Which one of you is going to be
the first one to be launched into space?

01:38:11.200 --> 01:38:12.679
Here he is.

01:38:13.280 --> 01:38:15.077
Captain Ham.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:19.560
Grinning like a possum
eating a sweet potato.

01:38:22.120 --> 01:38:25.749
Does he look like the kind of guy
who'd put doo-doo in the capsule?

01:38:26.920 --> 01:38:27.989
Ham in a can.

01:38:30.320 --> 01:38:32.709
America's first astronaut. Look at him!

01:38:33.720 --> 01:38:38.396
You take a monkey like this,
you can make him into a great astronaut.

01:38:40.080 --> 01:38:42.674
I think he's better looking than Crossfield.

01:38:45.200 --> 01:38:48.590
How would you like to go up
with this guy as your copilot?

01:39:55.600 --> 01:39:57.397
They've got a man up there. It's Gagarin.

01:39:57.480 --> 01:39:58.879
We know. Sit down.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:34.877
All right, give them a break.

01:40:39.760 --> 01:40:42.672
Is it true you were ready to go
and the flight was cancelled?

01:40:42.760 --> 01:40:44.910
Is it true we could've beaten the Russians?

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:48.037
Why didn't we send a man up
instead of a monkey?

01:40:49.640 --> 01:40:51.278
I think we ought to be...

01:40:51.560 --> 01:40:54.597
...forthright, gracious,
and magnanimous and say...

01:40:54.920 --> 01:40:57.309
...the Russians beat the pants off us.

01:40:57.560 --> 01:40:59.391
No sense in kidding ourselves about it.

01:40:59.480 --> 01:41:02.517
But the space age has begun,
and there's plenty of work.

01:41:02.600 --> 01:41:04.750
Who will be the second man in space?

01:41:05.640 --> 01:41:08.837
You mean who will be
the first free man into space?

01:41:09.840 --> 01:41:12.115
We know it'll be Glenn. Just tell us when.

01:41:12.400 --> 01:41:13.469
That's a secret.

01:41:14.760 --> 01:41:17.957
I'm tired of being "forthright,
gracious, and magnanimous."

01:41:18.360 --> 01:41:20.999
I'm tired of stupid questions
from the press.

01:41:21.400 --> 01:41:24.278
I'm tired of smocks,
of engineers telling us what we can't do.

01:41:24.360 --> 01:41:26.828
I'm tired of everybody saying
we are not pilots.

01:41:26.920 --> 01:41:28.512
I'm tired of monkeys.

01:41:29.000 --> 01:41:32.197
Most of all, I'm sick and tired
of being second to those...

01:41:32.840 --> 01:41:35.400
...those darned Russians. It's time we--

01:41:35.520 --> 01:41:36.999
Got someone up there!

01:41:39.280 --> 01:41:40.235
Fucking A, bubba.

01:41:40.520 --> 01:41:41.839
-Exactly.
-Let's talk to them.

01:41:41.920 --> 01:41:43.672
Let's get this thing on the road.

01:41:43.760 --> 01:41:45.591
I'm tired of messing around.

01:41:46.560 --> 01:41:49.438
We'll just tell 'em we're ready.
We're ready to go.

01:42:24.720 --> 01:42:28.872
In these three weeks since the Russian
Gagarin's flight surprised everybody...

01:42:29.040 --> 01:42:31.474
...one wretched event
has followed another.

01:42:31.600 --> 01:42:34.353
People have begun to say
our rockets always blow up...

01:42:34.440 --> 01:42:36.510
...our boys always botch it.

01:42:36.600 --> 01:42:41.674
Some say this is not the time to try
desperate deeds to beat the Soviets.

01:42:41.880 --> 01:42:43.108
The question really is:

01:42:43.200 --> 01:42:46.317
Are we actually ready
to launch a man into space?

01:42:46.520 --> 01:42:50.195
And yet out here at this very moment
sits a rocket, waiting in the night.

01:42:50.280 --> 01:42:53.477
Soon, one American astronaut
will climb atop that rocket...

01:42:53.560 --> 01:42:57.155
...in what may be the greatest
death-defying stunt ever broadcast.

01:43:00.480 --> 01:43:03.677
The identity of America's first astronaut
has been kept a secret...

01:43:03.760 --> 01:43:05.716
...until almost the final moment.

01:43:05.800 --> 01:43:09.236
The question everyone has asked is:
Which one will be first?

01:44:38.360 --> 01:44:39.873
Not very funny, John.

01:44:42.200 --> 01:44:44.270
But I do appreciate it, John.

01:44:44.760 --> 01:44:46.352
I surely do.

01:44:48.560 --> 01:44:50.630
Vaya con Dios, José.

01:45:00.080 --> 01:45:02.958
Dear Lord, please don't let me fuck up.

01:45:03.280 --> 01:45:05.874
I didn't quite copy that. Say again, please.

01:45:08.240 --> 01:45:10.196
I said, everything's A-okay.

01:45:10.360 --> 01:45:12.715
Well, that's what I thought you said.

01:45:14.040 --> 01:45:16.634
He said everything is A-okay.

01:45:17.600 --> 01:45:21.229
He says everything is A-okay.
And there you have it.

01:45:30.680 --> 01:45:33.717
Roger. Auto retro-jettison switch.

01:45:35.880 --> 01:45:37.836
Retro-heater switch...off.

01:45:39.640 --> 01:45:41.551
Retro-heater switch...off.

01:45:42.120 --> 01:45:44.429
Landing-bag switch...auto.

01:45:45.600 --> 01:45:48.990
Roger. Landing-bag switch...auto.

01:45:50.120 --> 01:45:52.839
This is it, ladies. This is for Life magazine.

01:45:56.400 --> 01:45:59.312
My God! They're going
after the diaper-service man.

01:46:06.360 --> 01:46:08.555
We don't have a diaper-service man.

01:46:12.480 --> 01:46:13.993
Oh, Louise, your lawn!

01:46:19.920 --> 01:46:21.273
Why are they here?

01:46:21.400 --> 01:46:22.799
What do they want?

01:46:22.880 --> 01:46:25.599
We are here live at the house
of Louise Shepard...

01:46:25.680 --> 01:46:29.116
...wife of Astronaut Al Shepard,
who is about to go into space.

01:46:34.640 --> 01:46:36.915
Wanted to keep you informed,
Mrs. Shepard.

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:39.434
Everything's A-okay.
Nothing to worry about.

01:46:39.720 --> 01:46:40.835
Just some delays.

01:46:41.200 --> 01:46:42.952
What kind of delays?

01:46:43.400 --> 01:46:46.119
There's another hold from NASA,
another delay.

01:46:46.440 --> 01:46:49.318
And Alan Shepard sits there
patiently waiting.

01:46:49.640 --> 01:46:52.677
What can be going through
a man's mind at this moment?

01:47:01.320 --> 01:47:02.719
I have to urinate.

01:47:02.800 --> 01:47:03.915
Urinate?

01:47:05.960 --> 01:47:08.394
Urinate? No. We did not think of that.

01:47:08.520 --> 01:47:10.750
This is only a 15-minute flight.

01:47:10.920 --> 01:47:12.990
The man's been up there for hours.

01:47:13.160 --> 01:47:14.718
Could he do it in his suit?

01:47:14.800 --> 01:47:17.360
It might be dangerous.
To introduce liquid...

01:47:17.520 --> 01:47:21.308
...into the pure oxygen of the capsule
and the pressure suit...

01:47:21.560 --> 01:47:24.518
...might cause a short circuit.
It could start a fire.

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:26.272
No. Tell him he cannot.

01:47:30.440 --> 01:47:34.433
Listen, old buddy, they promise
we'll stop at the next gas station.

01:47:34.920 --> 01:47:38.435
Request that you remain
in a holding pattern till then.

01:47:49.320 --> 01:47:52.232
-You sure you just want a little smidgen?
-About a half a cup.

01:47:52.320 --> 01:47:54.311
-And nothing in it?
-That's fine.

01:47:54.440 --> 01:47:55.475
All right.

01:47:57.560 --> 01:48:01.155
Alan had four cups of coffee
before he went to work this morning.

01:48:08.040 --> 01:48:10.429
All this waiting is driving me crazy.

01:48:13.800 --> 01:48:15.392
I had a little accident.

01:48:33.160 --> 01:48:35.549
Request permission to relieve bladder.

01:48:45.400 --> 01:48:47.709
Look, the man has got to go.

01:48:49.640 --> 01:48:52.996
It's either that or we get the lug wrench
and pry him out.

01:48:54.280 --> 01:48:55.713
Do it in the suit.

01:49:00.680 --> 01:49:02.716
José, permission granted...

01:49:02.800 --> 01:49:04.995
...to wet your diapers anytime, son.

01:49:16.840 --> 01:49:20.037
Suit thermometer says
Freon flow jumping from 30 to 45.

01:49:20.400 --> 01:49:22.277
Left lower-chest sensor.

01:49:26.600 --> 01:49:28.670
No shortout. Moving up back.

01:49:32.680 --> 01:49:33.715
Well....

01:49:34.200 --> 01:49:35.713
I'm a wetback now.

01:49:38.120 --> 01:49:40.111
It is questionable if we can proceed.

01:49:40.200 --> 01:49:44.512
I'm cooler than you are. Why don't you
fix your problems and light this candle!

01:49:44.840 --> 01:49:47.229
He's right! Let's light this candle!

01:49:47.400 --> 01:49:49.470
He surely is! Light the candle!

01:49:50.800 --> 01:49:52.313
Resume the countdown.

01:50:00.360 --> 01:50:01.713
T minus ten seconds...

01:50:01.800 --> 01:50:04.473
...nine, eight, seven....

01:50:11.960 --> 01:50:12.995
Ignition.

01:50:21.160 --> 01:50:22.878
You're on your way, José.

01:50:23.480 --> 01:50:26.074
We have liftoff, and the clock is operating.

01:50:34.720 --> 01:50:37.917
I think we'll be able to talk
to one of the astronaut wives...

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:40.150
...if not to Louise Shepard herself.

01:51:04.640 --> 01:51:09.077
He has re-entered the Earth's atmosphere
and the g-forces should be building up.

01:51:09.160 --> 01:51:11.355
Louise, he's coming down!

01:51:13.200 --> 01:51:15.350
We almost missed this.

01:51:19.840 --> 01:51:20.955
Eight.

01:51:22.480 --> 01:51:23.913
That's nine.

01:51:24.880 --> 01:51:26.154
I'm okay!

01:52:15.040 --> 01:52:17.952
The Vice President,
who is Chairman of our Space Council...

01:52:18.040 --> 01:52:20.634
...and who bears great responsibilities
in this field...

01:52:20.720 --> 01:52:22.950
...the members of the House and Senate...

01:52:23.040 --> 01:52:26.032
...Space Committee,
who are here today to award you...

01:52:27.520 --> 01:52:30.478
...this decoration,
which has gone from the ground up.

01:52:54.360 --> 01:52:55.952
What was Jackie like?

01:52:57.000 --> 01:52:58.274
She's very nice.

01:52:58.360 --> 01:53:00.510
We talked about all kinds of things.

01:53:00.600 --> 01:53:02.192
My Gus goes up next.

01:53:02.520 --> 01:53:04.590
I can't wait to talk to Jackie after that.

01:53:04.680 --> 01:53:07.877
You'll love her. She's so nice.
We talked about the kids.

01:53:26.040 --> 01:53:27.758
Mr. Shepard, sign here.

01:53:32.640 --> 01:53:34.551
I never realized...

01:53:35.200 --> 01:53:39.671
...a gruff, mean son of a bitch like you
could be so popular.

01:53:41.280 --> 01:53:43.510
How'd you get to go up before me?

01:53:43.840 --> 01:53:45.910
Even before "Mr. Clean, the Marine."

01:53:46.720 --> 01:53:48.870
Charm, Hot Dog. Pure charm.

01:53:49.760 --> 01:53:51.034
Watch this.

01:53:52.960 --> 01:53:54.791
Hey, sis, how are you doing?

01:53:54.880 --> 01:53:56.552
So-so. How are you doing?

01:53:56.960 --> 01:53:58.473
I ain't doing anymore.

01:53:58.560 --> 01:54:01.597
Damn thing's dragging in the mud,
and I can't get it up.

01:54:02.400 --> 01:54:04.356
Charm, Gus, that's pure charm.

01:54:07.360 --> 01:54:09.191
How'd you like one of these?

01:54:09.760 --> 01:54:12.149
I can get one of those from a dime store.

01:54:12.360 --> 01:54:14.715
Not one that's been in outer space.

01:54:15.360 --> 01:54:17.590
I'm taking these up with me tomorrow.

01:54:18.400 --> 01:54:21.597
Would you like a souvenir
after I get written in history?

01:54:21.880 --> 01:54:24.792
Well, I might, if it's been in outer space.

01:54:25.600 --> 01:54:27.511
See you after outer space.

01:54:38.240 --> 01:54:40.470
You got to think ahead to the future.

01:54:41.120 --> 01:54:43.998
Folks have a taste for things
that have been there.

01:54:46.560 --> 01:54:50.872
I'll give you one of these dimes
I'm taking up so you can play with it...

01:54:52.320 --> 01:54:54.550
...and dream about outer space.

01:54:56.960 --> 01:55:00.316
Why don't you just make sure
you don't screw the pooch?

01:55:04.320 --> 01:55:06.231
Oh, God, look at this.

01:55:14.520 --> 01:55:15.873
Go get 'em, Deke!

01:55:26.640 --> 01:55:29.871
Grissom has just reached the apex
of his flight into outer space...

01:55:29.960 --> 01:55:32.349
...and will be coming down
with the valuable data...

01:55:32.440 --> 01:55:35.716
...needed for the future flights
that will actually orbit the Earth.

01:55:35.800 --> 01:55:38.519
He will be re-entering the atmosphere now.

01:56:18.200 --> 01:56:22.830
Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7,
this is Hunt Club 1. Over.

01:56:23.480 --> 01:56:26.199
We're in orbit at this time
around the capsule.

01:56:29.400 --> 01:56:31.630
Are you ready to come in and hook on?

01:56:32.760 --> 01:56:34.990
Roger. This is Hunt Club 1...

01:56:35.240 --> 01:56:37.959
...waiting for your okay
to come in and hook on.

01:56:43.240 --> 01:56:47.438
Roger. I've unplugged my suit,
so I'm kind of warm now.

01:56:49.240 --> 01:56:50.992
Hunt Club 1. Roger.

01:56:51.320 --> 01:56:52.594
One, roger.

01:56:52.920 --> 01:56:55.798
Roger. Blow the hatch after we hook on.

01:56:56.800 --> 01:56:59.792
All right, get ready.
Another 15 feet to the right.

01:57:03.480 --> 01:57:05.948
If you're ready for me to blow the hatch...

01:57:06.680 --> 01:57:08.591
...I'll take my helmet off.

01:57:10.200 --> 01:57:11.758
Say again, Liberty Bell.

01:57:11.840 --> 01:57:14.149
Waiting for your okay to hook on.

01:57:18.040 --> 01:57:19.632
Who designed this?

01:57:20.920 --> 01:57:23.480
Say again, Liberty Bell. We can't hear you.

01:57:23.640 --> 01:57:25.073
I can't get it off.

01:57:27.720 --> 01:57:29.995
Liberty Bell, say again.

01:57:30.160 --> 01:57:32.628
This is Hunt Club 1, waiting for your okay.

01:57:39.760 --> 01:57:40.954
What happened?

01:57:43.640 --> 01:57:46.677
It's all right. He's okay.
Go for the capsule.

01:57:47.000 --> 01:57:48.592
Help, I'm sinking!

01:57:49.960 --> 01:57:52.520
Get the capsule. He can float in that suit.

01:57:56.440 --> 01:57:58.431
We need the data in the capsule.

01:57:58.520 --> 01:58:00.272
Throw down a line!

01:58:10.080 --> 01:58:12.594
Help! Throw down the line!

01:58:15.400 --> 01:58:16.992
Hey, I'm sinking!

01:58:17.320 --> 01:58:19.072
Forget the fucking capsule!

01:58:23.240 --> 01:58:25.470
We can't pull it. It's full of water.

01:58:26.280 --> 01:58:28.840
Hey! Help me over here!

01:58:34.840 --> 01:58:35.989
We've lost it!

01:58:36.080 --> 01:58:37.479
Blow the cable!

01:58:41.680 --> 01:58:43.318
Come back here, damn it!

01:58:53.680 --> 01:58:55.432
Throw a line down.

01:59:50.560 --> 01:59:52.073
I didn't do anything.

01:59:53.200 --> 01:59:54.838
I was just lying there.

01:59:55.600 --> 01:59:56.874
It just blew.

02:00:00.600 --> 02:00:02.238
The hatch just blew.

02:00:14.320 --> 02:00:17.039
It must have been a technical malfunction.

02:00:18.480 --> 02:00:20.710
The capsule was rocking around a bit.

02:00:21.040 --> 02:00:25.192
There were no loose items. I don't see
how I could have hit that button.

02:00:26.720 --> 02:00:29.188
I was just lying there, flat on my back...

02:00:29.360 --> 02:00:30.793
...and it just blew.

02:00:43.200 --> 02:00:45.430
Well, what do you think?

02:00:48.800 --> 02:00:52.315
Explosive hatches have been
on jet fighters for ten years.

02:00:52.800 --> 02:00:55.189
The things have been wrung inside out...

02:00:55.440 --> 02:00:59.433
...subjected to trial by heat,
by water, by shaking, pounding.

02:00:59.960 --> 02:01:04.715
We even drop them from a height
of 100 feet onto concrete...

02:01:05.680 --> 02:01:09.195
...and not one of them
has ever "just blown."

02:02:18.600 --> 02:02:20.830
Are we going to the White House?

02:02:23.280 --> 02:02:25.191
Isn't the President coming?

02:02:30.800 --> 02:02:33.030
No ticker-tape parade in New York?

02:02:35.440 --> 02:02:37.829
Not even one in Mitchell, Indiana?

02:02:43.400 --> 02:02:44.674
No Jackie?

02:02:53.600 --> 02:02:56.512
By order of the President
of the United States...

02:02:57.480 --> 02:02:59.869
...the Distinguished Service Medal...

02:03:00.480 --> 02:03:04.155
...is awarded to Captain Virgil I. Grissom...

02:03:06.080 --> 02:03:10.551
...who distinguished himself by valor
above and beyond the call of duty.

02:03:11.880 --> 02:03:13.279
These actions...

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:16.275
...reflect great credit upon himself...

02:03:17.000 --> 02:03:18.592
...the Air Force...

02:03:19.640 --> 02:03:22.359
...and the United States of America.

02:03:34.760 --> 02:03:36.034
You proud, boys?

02:03:46.360 --> 02:03:49.432
Hey, look. They filled up the refrigerator.

02:03:52.280 --> 02:03:53.633
Pretty good, huh?

02:03:54.720 --> 02:03:55.835
Pretty good.

02:03:56.440 --> 02:03:58.032
A full refrigerator!

02:03:59.520 --> 02:04:02.159
I can see this afternoon
is shaping up just great!

02:04:02.560 --> 02:04:05.028
And the rest of the day. Tomorrow, too!

02:04:05.760 --> 02:04:08.149
What do they want me to do in here?

02:04:08.680 --> 02:04:09.749
Cook?

02:04:10.960 --> 02:04:13.349
Then risk my life and my kids'...

02:04:13.440 --> 02:04:17.228
...by dragging them across that highway
to the worst beach in Florida!

02:04:18.080 --> 02:04:20.833
Oh, Gus, I wanted to eat
in the White House.

02:04:21.960 --> 02:04:24.190
I wanted to talk to Jackie about...

02:04:25.720 --> 02:04:26.869
...things.

02:04:28.560 --> 02:04:31.916
Well, look, I've got to go
to the Holiday Inn for some...

02:04:32.840 --> 02:04:34.558
...beer call with the guys.

02:04:38.960 --> 02:04:41.269
All those years of test flying...

02:04:42.320 --> 02:04:46.233
...and all those times I waited
and all those times you weren't there!

02:04:47.920 --> 02:04:49.751
The military promised...

02:04:50.320 --> 02:04:54.199
...and now they are welshing
on that damn compact.

02:04:55.200 --> 02:04:57.760
Look, I am finally
"Mrs. Honorable Astronaut."

02:04:58.200 --> 02:05:00.316
But they are treating me like I'm...

02:05:02.080 --> 02:05:04.469
...Honorable
"Mrs. Squirming Hatch Blower!"

02:05:04.640 --> 02:05:06.392
I didn't do anything wrong!

02:05:06.720 --> 02:05:11.191
The hatch just blew! It was a glitch!
It was a technical malfunction!

02:05:11.520 --> 02:05:13.750
Why in hell won't anyone believe me?

02:05:20.320 --> 02:05:21.912
I know that.

02:05:27.200 --> 02:05:29.998
Gus, I mean are these the goodies?

02:05:31.520 --> 02:05:33.829
Is this how the military pays off?

02:05:38.880 --> 02:05:41.599
Oh, Gus, they owe you.

02:05:44.520 --> 02:05:46.078
But they owe me, too.

02:05:47.480 --> 02:05:48.799
They owe me.

02:05:49.680 --> 02:05:52.148
They owe me, they owe me so much!

02:06:32.480 --> 02:06:33.754
I love you.

02:06:37.280 --> 02:06:41.398
We are here with Virgil I. Grissom
and his lovely wife, Betty.

02:06:42.680 --> 02:06:45.240
Gus has just come back
from the second trip in space.

02:06:45.320 --> 02:06:47.595
Betty, how do you feel about this trip?

02:06:47.840 --> 02:06:49.432
I'm so proud of him.

02:06:49.760 --> 02:06:51.398
I think he was wonderful.

02:06:51.520 --> 02:06:53.590
We're all proud of Gus Grissom.

02:06:53.760 --> 02:06:56.797
Gus, how do you feel about the trip?
Was it a success?

02:06:57.120 --> 02:06:58.712
It was A-okay.

02:07:01.240 --> 02:07:04.357
My God. He lost his capsule
but he's keeping his story.

02:07:04.480 --> 02:07:06.596
To recap yesterday's dramatic events...

02:07:06.880 --> 02:07:09.678
...here we see America's
newest hero, Gus Grissom.

02:07:09.760 --> 02:07:12.194
He is shouting to save the capsule first.

02:07:13.440 --> 02:07:16.432
Pull that in flight test, it's all over for him.

02:07:17.800 --> 02:07:20.758
He screwed the pooch, partner.
Plain and simple.

02:07:21.320 --> 02:07:24.232
Sometimes you get a pooch
that can't be screwed.

02:07:26.320 --> 02:07:29.118
The President's got his own problems
with the Bay of Pigs.

02:07:29.200 --> 02:07:31.395
He doesn't want
the astronauts' image tarnished.

02:07:31.480 --> 02:07:34.313
Nothing these guys do
is going to be called a failure.

02:07:34.400 --> 02:07:36.197
These astronauts are our Davids.

02:07:36.280 --> 02:07:40.273
You think the public would know they're
just doing what monkeys have done.

02:07:43.920 --> 02:07:47.629
You think a monkey knows he's sitting
on a rocket that might explode?

02:07:48.720 --> 02:07:50.836
These astronauts know that.

02:07:52.840 --> 02:07:54.432
I'll tell you something.

02:07:55.000 --> 02:07:57.878
It takes a special man to volunteer
for a suicide mission.

02:07:57.960 --> 02:07:59.678
Especially when it's on TV.

02:08:03.800 --> 02:08:05.711
Old Gus, he did all right.

02:08:06.120 --> 02:08:08.190
Though the capsule was lost,
our new hero...

02:08:08.280 --> 02:08:10.430
...Astronaut Gus Grissom, was saved.

02:08:11.160 --> 02:08:15.153
Now President Kennedy has started
an even more ambitious space program.

02:08:15.480 --> 02:08:17.391
Those who came before us...

02:08:17.920 --> 02:08:19.672
...made certain this country...

02:08:19.760 --> 02:08:23.116
...rode the first waves
of the industrial revolution...

02:08:24.120 --> 02:08:26.634
...the first waves of modern invention...

02:08:26.720 --> 02:08:29.029
...and the first wave of nuclear power.

02:08:29.120 --> 02:08:31.998
And this generation does not intend...

02:08:32.520 --> 02:08:34.511
...to founder in the backwash...

02:08:34.800 --> 02:08:38.156
...of the coming age of space.
We mean to be a part of it.

02:08:38.520 --> 02:08:39.953
We mean to lead it.

02:10:32.800 --> 02:10:35.030
You know, I always hated flying.

02:10:37.800 --> 02:10:41.873
When I met you, you were already a pilot,
so I never had a complaint coming.

02:10:43.200 --> 02:10:46.158
When you went up in those planes,
me and the kids....

02:10:51.320 --> 02:10:54.630
We never had any insurance
except a couple months' pay.

02:10:56.880 --> 02:10:59.474
I always hated all that talk
about insurance.

02:11:01.240 --> 02:11:04.550
The government spends
all kinds of time and money...

02:11:04.640 --> 02:11:07.200
...teaching pilots how to be fearless.

02:11:09.840 --> 02:11:12.912
But they don't spend a penny
teaching you how to be...

02:11:13.720 --> 02:11:15.950
...the fearless wife of a test pilot.

02:11:20.760 --> 02:11:22.512
But I guess I liked it.

02:11:28.760 --> 02:11:31.274
I guess I liked the kind of man who could...

02:11:32.280 --> 02:11:34.430
...push the outside of the envelope.

02:11:37.080 --> 02:11:38.195
Flyboy.

02:11:41.240 --> 02:11:45.711
But I never could stand a man
who was one of those "remember-whens."

02:11:46.360 --> 02:11:50.399
Those bitter guys that just sit around
thinking about old times.

02:11:57.080 --> 02:11:58.911
If I ever see that happen...

02:12:02.680 --> 02:12:04.910
...I'm going right out the front door.

02:12:09.120 --> 02:12:10.838
And you'll never catch me.

02:12:12.440 --> 02:12:15.318
I'm a fearless man,
but I'm scared to death of you.

02:12:15.640 --> 02:12:17.232
No, you're not.

02:12:18.600 --> 02:12:20.079
But you ought to be.

02:12:41.320 --> 02:12:42.594
What is it?

02:12:44.120 --> 02:12:46.076
The Russians have sent Titov up.

02:12:46.200 --> 02:12:47.315
Titov's up.

02:12:47.920 --> 02:12:48.830
How long?

02:12:48.920 --> 02:12:49.875
A day.

02:12:50.200 --> 02:12:52.430
A day? A whole day?

02:12:52.600 --> 02:12:54.989
He's orbiting over our country right now.

02:12:55.840 --> 02:12:58.195
We need a man in orbit or it's all over.

02:12:58.520 --> 02:13:01.478
We're scrapping the Redstone
and going with the Atlas.

02:13:01.560 --> 02:13:03.232
You know what that means.

02:13:03.600 --> 02:13:06.160
We haven't had too much luck
with that rocket.

02:13:06.480 --> 02:13:09.040
We can't take all the precautions we'd like.

02:13:09.440 --> 02:13:11.158
-It'll be dangerous.
-We're ready.

02:13:11.240 --> 02:13:12.912
I said it'll be dangerous.

02:13:13.000 --> 02:13:15.389
I said we're ready. 100 percent.

02:13:28.920 --> 02:13:32.754
Inside this trim,
modest suburban home is Annie Glenn...

02:13:33.080 --> 02:13:35.116
...wife of Astronaut John Glenn...

02:13:35.400 --> 02:13:39.598
...sharing the anxiety and pride
of the world at this tense moment...

02:13:40.000 --> 02:13:43.788
...but in a private and crucial way
that only she can understand.

02:13:50.360 --> 02:13:53.557
The Vice President would like
to see Mrs. Glenn.

02:13:54.040 --> 02:13:55.758
He's asking for you again.

02:13:56.760 --> 02:13:58.352
Tell them no.

02:13:59.000 --> 02:14:00.911
I'm sorry, she says no.

02:14:01.040 --> 02:14:03.031
You don't understand. It is very important.

02:14:03.120 --> 02:14:05.076
The Vice President must see her.

02:14:07.640 --> 02:14:10.029
We are told after the mission's success...

02:14:10.120 --> 02:14:13.556
...the Vice President will come here
and speak with Annie Glenn.

02:14:14.040 --> 02:14:17.191
Meanwhile, John Glenn waits
for the weather to clear...

02:14:17.280 --> 02:14:19.840
...so he can undertake this historic mission.

02:14:20.360 --> 02:14:22.351
You know what the Russians want?

02:14:24.840 --> 02:14:27.479
They want our peckers in their pockets.

02:14:30.960 --> 02:14:32.359
She still says no.

02:14:34.000 --> 02:14:37.515
Didn't you tell her I'll bring in ABC-TV...

02:14:38.000 --> 02:14:40.639
...NBC-TV, CBS-TV?

02:14:41.640 --> 02:14:44.837
Her words, and mine,
will be heard by millions.

02:14:54.360 --> 02:14:55.873
Where are they going?

02:14:57.920 --> 02:14:59.876
I think the flight's been cancelled.

02:14:59.960 --> 02:15:01.154
Cancelled?

02:15:03.920 --> 02:15:05.399
That's perfect.

02:15:05.720 --> 02:15:09.395
I will go in and console her
on nationwide TV.

02:15:10.520 --> 02:15:12.431
I'll pay her a sympathy call.

02:15:39.960 --> 02:15:43.919
The Vice President would like to make
a sympathy call if he could.

02:15:47.320 --> 02:15:49.754
-No? What do you mean, "No"?
-I mean, "No."

02:15:50.200 --> 02:15:52.270
What do you mean, "No"?

02:15:52.600 --> 02:15:54.636
Somebody get NASA on the line.

02:15:54.800 --> 02:15:58.839
I'm going to lean on NASA.
I'm going right to the top!

02:16:00.040 --> 02:16:01.632
-To the top.
-Damn right!

02:16:02.040 --> 02:16:04.554
They better tell her to play ball!

02:16:13.080 --> 02:16:14.911
There's a problem with your wife.

02:16:15.000 --> 02:16:16.752
-Is it serious?
-We think it is.

02:16:16.840 --> 02:16:19.354
There's a phone hook-up,
we've got her on it.

02:16:27.760 --> 02:16:29.876
It's me. Are you all right?

02:16:29.960 --> 02:16:31.234
What's wrong?

02:16:31.640 --> 02:16:33.232
Johnson...

02:16:35.320 --> 02:16:36.912
...wants...me...

02:16:40.600 --> 02:16:42.750
...on T...V.

02:16:43.120 --> 02:16:44.348
The Vice President?

02:16:44.440 --> 02:16:46.715
Tell her to let him in with the networks.

02:16:46.799 --> 02:16:48.119
It's coverage.

02:16:52.440 --> 02:16:53.998
It's important, John.

02:16:54.559 --> 02:16:55.788
It means a lot.

02:17:01.600 --> 02:17:02.749
Listen to me.

02:17:05.000 --> 02:17:07.308
If you don't want the Vice President...

02:17:07.680 --> 02:17:10.911
...or the networks,
or anyone else in our house, that's it!

02:17:11.360 --> 02:17:14.079
As far as I'm concerned,
they are not coming in!

02:17:14.160 --> 02:17:17.391
And I will back you up 100 percent,
and you tell them that!

02:17:19.240 --> 02:17:23.153
I don't want Johnson or the others
to even put a toe in our house.

02:17:29.639 --> 02:17:33.871
You tell them that Astronaut John Glenn
told you to say that.

02:17:42.120 --> 02:17:43.871
I'll talk to you soon.

02:17:49.320 --> 02:17:50.673
You can't do that!

02:17:50.760 --> 02:17:52.591
The Vice President's head of the program!

02:17:52.719 --> 02:17:54.438
You must think of the program!

02:17:54.520 --> 02:17:55.794
You are out of line!

02:17:55.920 --> 02:17:57.911
-I'm out of line?
-Yes, sir!

02:17:59.080 --> 02:18:00.308
I run the show here.

02:18:00.400 --> 02:18:02.038
We'll see about that!

02:18:02.440 --> 02:18:05.796
And I'm thinking of changing
the order of flight assignments!

02:18:06.600 --> 02:18:07.952
Who will you get?

02:18:08.200 --> 02:18:10.111
You heard what he said.

02:18:15.520 --> 02:18:17.111
Take it easy, fellows.

02:18:17.480 --> 02:18:18.913
Step aside, pal.

02:18:30.440 --> 02:18:31.714
Pilots!

02:18:35.000 --> 02:18:36.911
Pansies! Cows!

02:18:39.559 --> 02:18:40.993
Gladiolas!

02:18:41.320 --> 02:18:45.029
Isn't there anybody
who can deal with a housewife?

02:19:10.120 --> 02:19:12.759
Waltzing Matilda,
I thought Hank Williams wrote it.

02:19:12.840 --> 02:19:14.671
We don't know who wrote it.

02:19:14.760 --> 02:19:16.397
It's Australian, right?

02:19:24.840 --> 02:19:26.432
Who are you guys?

02:19:29.760 --> 02:19:31.112
We're aborigines.

02:19:36.520 --> 02:19:37.555
Who are you?

02:19:37.639 --> 02:19:38.629
Me?

02:19:41.080 --> 02:19:42.433
I'm an astronaut.

02:19:46.280 --> 02:19:48.840
Well, what do you do here, Astronaut?

02:19:49.440 --> 02:19:53.433
I'm here because a buddy of mine
is getting ready to...

02:19:54.120 --> 02:19:56.680
...fly overhead. Up in outer space.

02:19:57.160 --> 02:19:59.720
And I'll be talking to him on that dish.

02:20:00.760 --> 02:20:01.875
Fly over?

02:20:02.680 --> 02:20:04.272
You blokes do that, too?

02:20:05.120 --> 02:20:06.758
You do that yourself?

02:20:07.200 --> 02:20:09.156
Not me, mate.

02:20:09.880 --> 02:20:11.518
See that old bloke there?

02:20:13.080 --> 02:20:14.035
He know.

02:20:14.280 --> 02:20:15.713
He know the moon.

02:20:16.520 --> 02:20:17.953
He know the star.

02:20:18.960 --> 02:20:20.837
And he know the Milky Way.

02:20:21.320 --> 02:20:23.117
He'll give you a hand.

02:20:24.200 --> 02:20:25.315
He know.

02:20:29.320 --> 02:20:32.039
We're gonna need all the help we can get.

02:21:00.840 --> 02:21:03.400
Stand by for final ten-second count.

02:22:02.440 --> 02:22:04.192
The clock is operating.

02:22:05.120 --> 02:22:06.872
We're underway!

02:22:11.880 --> 02:22:15.555
Good Lord, ride all the way.
Godspeed, John Glenn.

02:23:27.240 --> 02:23:29.629
Zero-g, and I feel fine.

02:23:31.400 --> 02:23:33.630
The capsule is turning around.

02:23:37.000 --> 02:23:38.911
The view is tremendous!

02:23:39.120 --> 02:23:43.352
I can see clear back,
a big cloud pattern, towards the Cape.

02:23:43.440 --> 02:23:45.237
It's a beautiful sight!

02:23:45.640 --> 02:23:49.918
Roger, Friendship 7.
You have a go, at least seven orbits.

02:23:54.280 --> 02:23:57.238
Roger, Al. Understand,
go at least seven orbits.

02:23:57.320 --> 02:23:58.912
This is Friendship 7.

02:24:24.080 --> 02:24:27.436
Speed is 17,500 miles per hour...

02:24:35.240 --> 02:24:37.470
...and we're moving into night.

02:24:57.560 --> 02:24:59.312
Full moon rising.

02:25:03.240 --> 02:25:04.992
I can almost touch it.

02:25:19.880 --> 02:25:22.599
Friendship 7, come in. Do you read?

02:25:26.080 --> 02:25:27.957
Friendship 7, come in, please.

02:25:28.360 --> 02:25:30.078
This sure was a short day.

02:25:30.240 --> 02:25:31.878
Say again, please. Over.

02:25:32.360 --> 02:25:34.920
That was the shortest day I've run into.

02:25:35.400 --> 02:25:37.311
Kind of passes rapidly, huh?

02:25:41.400 --> 02:25:44.437
I can see some lights down there
in Australia, Gordo.

02:25:45.120 --> 02:25:46.599
Where are they from?

02:25:46.920 --> 02:25:50.993
All of Perth and Rockingham
have turned their lights on for you.

02:25:52.320 --> 02:25:55.437
And we have a few other lights turned on,
here and there.

02:26:00.680 --> 02:26:02.398
They show up very well.

02:26:02.960 --> 02:26:05.679
Thank everybody for turning them on,
will you?

02:26:06.120 --> 02:26:08.839
We sure will, John. We sure will.

02:26:25.160 --> 02:26:26.912
Heading towards daybreak.

02:27:04.560 --> 02:27:06.755
Lot of cloud coverage today.

02:27:14.200 --> 02:27:15.872
Man, it's beautiful.

02:27:30.440 --> 02:27:32.351
Possibly it's the heat shield.

02:27:32.680 --> 02:27:33.795
It's loose.

02:27:36.440 --> 02:27:37.714
If it comes off--

02:27:37.800 --> 02:27:40.360
If the heat shield comes off, he'll burn up.

02:27:41.320 --> 02:27:43.390
He'll fry when he tries to re-enter.

02:27:57.800 --> 02:27:59.392
Muchea, this is Cape.

02:28:00.360 --> 02:28:02.112
We're showing some trouble.

02:28:02.320 --> 02:28:05.392
We've got a warning light.
Possibly a loose heat shield.

02:28:05.520 --> 02:28:07.750
Check your status lights immediately.

02:28:26.000 --> 02:28:27.399
He's coming.

02:28:29.240 --> 02:28:30.753
John, can you hear me?

02:28:33.160 --> 02:28:35.071
Friendship 7, come in, please.

02:28:35.360 --> 02:28:36.998
Try something. Anything.

02:28:37.080 --> 02:28:38.354
Friendship 7, come in.

02:29:11.800 --> 02:29:15.315
This is Friendship 7. Do you read me?

02:29:16.960 --> 02:29:18.393
Wait a second.

02:29:19.960 --> 02:29:22.190
I see something strange out here.

02:29:22.360 --> 02:29:25.557
Oh! My goodness, what the heck is that?

02:29:26.520 --> 02:29:29.557
Sparks and needles of some kind
all over the sky!

02:29:29.880 --> 02:29:32.917
Hey, let me tell you what I'm in up here.

02:29:33.240 --> 02:29:35.629
I'm in a mass of very small particles...

02:29:35.840 --> 02:29:38.991
...that are brilliantly lit up.
Like they're luminescent.

02:29:39.160 --> 02:29:41.071
I never saw anything like it.

02:29:41.560 --> 02:29:43.516
A shower of them coming by me now.

02:29:43.600 --> 02:29:46.592
They're bright yellow.
They swirl around the capsule...

02:29:46.680 --> 02:29:49.399
...and they're brilliantly lighted.

02:29:50.360 --> 02:29:53.079
Do you think they could be alive?

02:29:55.280 --> 02:29:58.829
It sounds ridiculous,
but they look like fireflies or something.

02:30:01.960 --> 02:30:04.918
Maybe some Air Force experiment
went amuck.

02:30:05.240 --> 02:30:07.470
Could our astronomers have been wrong?

02:30:07.800 --> 02:30:10.678
Hello, Capcom, do you read me?
This is miraculous!

02:30:11.520 --> 02:30:14.671
Could it be those fireflies,
or whatever they are?

02:30:15.160 --> 02:30:17.071
Of course not. Fireflies?

02:30:19.600 --> 02:30:21.238
Roger, Friendship 7.

02:30:22.840 --> 02:30:26.037
Will you correlate the actions
of the surrounding particles...

02:30:26.120 --> 02:30:28.190
...with that of your control jets?

02:30:29.760 --> 02:30:31.159
Negative.

02:30:31.800 --> 02:30:35.156
I do not think they were coming
from my control jets.

02:30:36.280 --> 02:30:38.191
I'll tell you what I'll try to do.

02:30:38.280 --> 02:30:40.999
I'll try to get some pictures
of these little guys.

02:30:41.080 --> 02:30:42.672
Sounds like a good idea.

02:30:43.120 --> 02:30:45.429
You guys probably think I'm nuts.

02:30:46.560 --> 02:30:48.278
They're very beautiful.

02:30:48.760 --> 02:30:50.716
Look like fireflies on a summer night.

02:30:50.800 --> 02:30:52.518
They just dance around.

02:31:28.680 --> 02:31:30.033
Get out of here!

02:31:32.680 --> 02:31:34.671
Get out of here, you gadgets!

02:31:37.200 --> 02:31:39.589
Heading into daybreak now. Another day.

02:31:39.800 --> 02:31:41.711
Leaving the fireflies behind.

02:31:41.960 --> 02:31:43.951
I have no idea what they were.

02:31:45.080 --> 02:31:46.672
This is Friendship 7.

02:31:47.720 --> 02:31:50.280
That was some night.
That was really exciting.

02:31:50.440 --> 02:31:51.919
He's going into his third orbit.

02:31:52.000 --> 02:31:54.992
How much longer are you going
to keep him in the dark?

02:31:55.440 --> 02:31:56.668
What do we tell him?

02:31:56.760 --> 02:31:59.718
He's a pilot.
Tell him the condition of his craft.

02:32:05.280 --> 02:32:06.838
Glenn is in his third orbit...

02:32:06.920 --> 02:32:09.559
...and the flight is going
pretty much as planned.

02:32:09.880 --> 02:32:11.199
No human individual...

02:32:11.280 --> 02:32:13.714
...has ever been so well prepared.

02:32:14.160 --> 02:32:17.675
So far the key word
on this textbook flight is ''operational. ''

02:32:17.800 --> 02:32:19.472
Everything is A-okay.

02:32:21.440 --> 02:32:24.273
We haven't been too lucky
with the Atlas rocket.

02:32:24.440 --> 02:32:27.910
Some say we haven't taken all
the safety precautions we'd like to.

02:32:28.000 --> 02:32:29.149
Is this true?

02:32:29.240 --> 02:32:30.958
No, it's absolutely not true.

02:32:31.480 --> 02:32:34.040
The only critical point is the re-entry.

02:32:34.480 --> 02:32:37.199
If the capsule is not at the correct angle...

02:32:37.280 --> 02:32:40.909
...with the blunt end and heat shield down,
it will burn up.

02:32:41.240 --> 02:32:42.992
There is only one hope.

02:32:43.360 --> 02:32:46.033
It might be possible to leave
the retro-rocket package...

02:32:46.120 --> 02:32:48.031
...which covers the heat shield, on.

02:32:48.520 --> 02:32:53.116
The straps may be strong enough
to hold the heat shield in place.

02:32:53.800 --> 02:32:55.552
But if this fails....

02:32:57.160 --> 02:33:00.197
John, you're going to
fly-by-wire for re-entry.

02:33:01.080 --> 02:33:04.595
We recommend you do the best
you can to keep a zero angle. Over.

02:33:05.360 --> 02:33:07.271
Re-entry only three orbits?

02:33:07.600 --> 02:33:09.079
That is correct.

02:33:09.160 --> 02:33:11.310
Do you have a reason for this?

02:33:11.600 --> 02:33:14.910
Not at this time.
This is the judgement of Cape Flight.

02:33:18.840 --> 02:33:22.037
Do you have a time for going
to jettison retro? Over.

02:33:24.440 --> 02:33:27.318
We are not sure your landing bag
is deployed.

02:33:27.960 --> 02:33:31.430
We feel it is possible to re-enter
with the retropackage on.

02:33:31.720 --> 02:33:35.110
We see no difficulty at this time
with that type of re-entry.

02:33:35.200 --> 02:33:36.599
Do you read?

02:33:37.440 --> 02:33:38.668
Roger.

02:33:39.960 --> 02:33:41.393
Understand.

02:33:42.680 --> 02:33:46.355
I'll start lining up as carefully as I can
in a minute.

02:33:46.760 --> 02:33:51.390
See whether scanners will pick up
and correct it for good retro-fire attitude.

02:33:52.240 --> 02:33:53.355
If not...

02:33:54.040 --> 02:33:55.951
...I'll correct it myself.

02:34:07.920 --> 02:34:09.399
We're lined up.

02:34:10.320 --> 02:34:11.639
Here we go.

02:34:48.760 --> 02:34:50.352
What's that sound?

02:34:50.640 --> 02:34:52.119
Humming. It's him.

02:34:52.200 --> 02:34:54.111
It's all right. He does that.

02:36:00.240 --> 02:36:01.593
He can't hear you.

02:36:01.840 --> 02:36:03.956
He's hit the ionization blackout.

02:36:04.880 --> 02:36:07.838
No communications are possible
for a few minutes.

02:36:10.440 --> 02:36:11.919
Then we'll know.

02:36:20.880 --> 02:36:23.440
Friendship 7, this is Cape. Do you read?

02:36:30.320 --> 02:36:32.390
This is Cape. Do you read?

02:36:36.880 --> 02:36:40.236
Friendship 7, this is Cape. Do you read?

02:36:40.640 --> 02:36:44.349
Automatic systems are not functioning.
He's in fly-by-wire--

02:37:44.960 --> 02:37:46.473
Finally showed up.

02:37:46.920 --> 02:37:49.115
The one with the big engine.

02:37:50.760 --> 02:37:53.672
Boy, if we'd only had
one of those a few years back.

02:37:54.840 --> 02:37:58.992
The bad news is the entire program's
probably going to be scrapped.

02:38:00.040 --> 02:38:03.749
From now on, the astronaut boys
in Houston have got the only ticket.

02:38:04.560 --> 02:38:08.075
Barring, of course, some unforeseen event.

02:38:28.920 --> 02:38:31.992
The Russians set a new record
of 1 14,000 feet...

02:38:32.080 --> 02:38:34.036
...going straight off the ground.

02:38:34.120 --> 02:38:36.714
Nobody cares about
that kind of record anymore.

02:38:37.400 --> 02:38:40.392
All they want now
is capsules up in outer space.

02:38:43.440 --> 02:38:47.433
I get a feeling this plane might be able
to beat that Russian record.

02:38:50.240 --> 02:38:51.753
You might be right.

02:39:37.600 --> 02:39:39.431
And here they come!

02:39:48.800 --> 02:39:51.712
Looky here what I brought you!

02:40:33.520 --> 02:40:34.794
Smile, hon.

02:40:35.760 --> 02:40:37.512
My fellow citizens...

02:40:40.080 --> 02:40:44.153
...America's Mercury astronauts!

02:40:55.400 --> 02:40:58.278
Welcome to Houston, your new home.

02:40:58.600 --> 02:41:03.151
Your neighbors here and I,
we'd like to give you this little barbecue...

02:41:05.600 --> 02:41:07.079
...Texas style!

02:41:48.720 --> 02:41:52.952
Since you're relocating here,
to show appreciation for all you've done...

02:41:53.320 --> 02:41:56.039
...Mr. Sharp is contributing the land...

02:41:56.120 --> 02:41:58.111
...the contractors the homes...

02:41:58.240 --> 02:42:01.073
...and department stores, the furnishings.

02:42:03.400 --> 02:42:04.753
Which one are you?

02:42:07.760 --> 02:42:10.274
Which one's Glenn? I want to meet him.

02:42:11.880 --> 02:42:13.359
He's over there.

02:42:22.320 --> 02:42:25.437
I'm going to the moon,
I swear to God, I'm on my way.

02:42:28.920 --> 02:42:31.753
Hi, little gal.
Damned glad to meet you, too.

02:42:31.920 --> 02:42:35.435
I heard an awful lot of good things
about you, gal.

02:42:44.640 --> 02:42:45.709
We got it.

02:42:46.120 --> 02:42:48.873
Steak. All the trimmings.

02:42:50.680 --> 02:42:52.557
Just like Pancho's.

02:42:55.280 --> 02:42:57.191
Steak tastes about the same...

02:42:57.960 --> 02:43:00.713
...only there's a lot
more trimmings now, Gus.

02:43:03.240 --> 02:43:04.753
You know, it's funny.

02:43:05.720 --> 02:43:09.918
Here I am, I got $25,000 a year
for a magazine contract.

02:43:10.840 --> 02:43:13.354
I got a free house with all the furnishings.

02:43:13.440 --> 02:43:15.112
Got me a Corvette.

02:43:16.080 --> 02:43:19.436
I got a free lunch from one end of America
to the other...

02:43:20.440 --> 02:43:22.670
...and I ain't even been up there yet.

02:43:24.800 --> 02:43:25.835
I noticed that.

02:43:25.920 --> 02:43:29.276
Oh, you noticed that?
You noticed I hadn't been up there yet?

02:43:31.960 --> 02:43:34.315
They're saving the best for last.

02:43:36.360 --> 02:43:38.920
Yeah, I guess so, Hot Dog. I guess so.

02:43:41.280 --> 02:43:43.510
Just watch you don't screw the pooch.

02:44:02.440 --> 02:44:06.831
We're talking to Gordon Cooper.
He will be the next to orbit the Earth.

02:44:08.680 --> 02:44:13.310
Since you're the last of the original seven
and the least well known...

02:44:13.600 --> 02:44:18.116
...could you begin by telling us
who was the best pilot you ever saw?

02:44:18.920 --> 02:44:21.229
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

02:44:28.400 --> 02:44:30.914
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

02:44:35.200 --> 02:44:36.713
I'll tell you.

02:44:36.960 --> 02:44:41.511
I've seen a lot of them,
and most of them were pictures on a wall--

02:44:42.760 --> 02:44:46.799
I said, "pictures on a wall,"
back at some place that...

02:44:48.960 --> 02:44:50.996
...doesn't even exist anymore.

02:44:54.040 --> 02:44:55.473
Some of them are...

02:44:55.600 --> 02:44:57.511
...right here in this room.

02:44:59.120 --> 02:45:00.872
And some of them are...

02:45:01.560 --> 02:45:05.553
...they're still out there somewhere,
doing what they always do.

02:45:05.680 --> 02:45:08.911
Going up each day
in a hurtling piece of machinery...

02:45:09.040 --> 02:45:11.759
...putting their hides out on the line...

02:45:12.160 --> 02:45:14.469
...hanging it out over the edge...

02:45:14.680 --> 02:45:18.309
...pushing back the outside
of that envelope and hauling it back.

02:45:20.320 --> 02:45:21.833
But there was...

02:45:22.400 --> 02:45:26.791
...one pilot I once saw who I think
truly did have the right--

02:45:26.880 --> 02:45:29.838
How close did you ever come
to not hauling it back?

02:45:34.960 --> 02:45:37.190
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

02:45:37.520 --> 02:45:39.590
Well, you're looking at him.

02:45:57.080 --> 02:45:58.832
You got any Beemans?

02:46:00.320 --> 02:46:01.992
I might have me a stick.

02:46:02.080 --> 02:46:04.719
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

02:46:06.400 --> 02:46:07.719
Fair enough.

02:46:09.040 --> 02:46:12.077
Think I see a plane over here
with my name on it.

02:46:14.280 --> 02:46:15.918
Now you're talking.

02:46:30.000 --> 02:46:31.433
Hey, what's that?

02:46:31.680 --> 02:46:33.511
Anyone got clearance?

02:46:37.120 --> 02:46:39.270
What kind of a plane is that?

02:46:44.960 --> 02:46:47.838
Aircraft on ramp, did you file a flight plan?

02:46:48.800 --> 02:46:51.758
Aircraft on ramp, did you file a flight plan?

02:46:52.400 --> 02:46:55.915
I'm taking her up to wring her out a bit.
Any objections?

02:46:56.040 --> 02:46:57.359
It's Yeager.

02:46:59.680 --> 02:47:01.113
No objections.

02:47:01.440 --> 02:47:03.271
You are clear to taxi.

02:47:04.800 --> 02:47:06.870
He must have clearance. Right?

02:47:07.040 --> 02:47:09.031
Yeah. Sure, he must.

02:47:09.600 --> 02:47:11.113
It's here someplace.

02:49:11.160 --> 02:49:13.310
Now, in honor of...

02:49:13.560 --> 02:49:17.189
...these, the greatest pilots
in the history of mankind...

02:49:17.680 --> 02:49:21.514
...it gives me great pleasure, great pride,
to present to you...

02:49:22.120 --> 02:49:23.872
...Miss Sally Rand!

02:52:09.480 --> 02:52:11.391
Stretch it! Stretch it!

02:52:12.400 --> 02:52:13.799
You can do it!

02:52:15.240 --> 02:52:18.596
Just a little bit more.
104,000, here you go.

02:52:23.960 --> 02:52:25.518
Christ Almighty!

02:55:36.800 --> 02:55:38.472
Sir, over there.

02:55:40.880 --> 02:55:42.279
Is that a man?

02:55:45.120 --> 02:55:47.190
Yeah, you're damn right it is!

02:56:51.320 --> 02:56:53.595
We hate to disturb you, buddy, but...

02:56:54.480 --> 02:56:55.993
...we've got a launch.

02:56:59.160 --> 02:57:02.596
There's millions of people watching,
and we thought maybe....

02:57:03.040 --> 02:57:05.952
Yep. Well, no sweat. Let's go.

02:57:06.680 --> 02:57:09.752
I'm ready when you are, John, 100 percent.

02:57:15.360 --> 02:57:17.271
Ten...nine....

02:57:57.880 --> 02:57:59.632
Go.

02:58:06.840 --> 02:58:09.070
Go, Hot Dog, go!

02:58:13.720 --> 02:58:16.280
"Up we go into the wild blue yonder."

02:58:16.680 --> 02:58:20.229
Thirty seconds and fuel is go,
oxygen is go...

02:58:20.320 --> 02:58:23.471
...cabin pressure on the top peg.
Altimeter is working.

02:58:25.240 --> 02:58:27.151
Have a good ride, buddy. Go!

02:58:31.680 --> 02:58:34.069
The sun is coming through the window.

02:58:35.800 --> 02:58:38.678
Oh, Lord, what a heavenly light.

02:58:50.800 --> 02:58:53.234
The Mercury program was over.

02:58:53.880 --> 02:58:57.077
Four years later,
Astronaut Gus Grissom was killed...

02:58:57.160 --> 02:58:59.799
...along with Astronauts White
and Chaffee...

02:58:59.920 --> 02:59:02.878
...when fire swept through
their Apollo capsule.

02:59:03.880 --> 02:59:07.634
But on that glorious day in May, 1963...

02:59:07.960 --> 02:59:11.350
...Gordo Cooper went higher, farther...

02:59:11.640 --> 02:59:14.029
...and faster than any other American.

02:59:14.520 --> 02:59:17.273
Twenty-two complete orbits
around the world.

02:59:17.560 --> 02:59:20.791
He was the last American
ever to go into space alone.

02:59:21.240 --> 02:59:23.071
And for a brief moment...

02:59:23.400 --> 02:59:28.269
...Gordo Cooper became the greatest pilot
anyone had ever seen.

